report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-year-old woman with a history of falling and hitting her head with loss of consciousness.  She is 30 weeks pregnant and fell again with loss of consciousness. While in the hospital, a nurse noticed twitching of her eyes with arm jerks.
MEDICATIONS: None listed.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 8.5 Hz, 50 V posterior dominant rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive. Brief drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements.
HR:  86 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing with sleep deprivation, hyperventilation, and photic stimulation would be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 72-year-old, right-handed gentleman with change in mental status, open heart transplant in 1999, previous stroke with mild residual left-sided weakness, past herpes zoster. CT of the head was negative.
MEDICATIONS: Haldol, Risperdal, Prednisone, Prevacid, aspirin, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is diffusely slow and low voltage.  When awake, there is a 6 to 7 Hz frequency with generalized background theta.  There are also brief bursts of frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity in wakefulness.
There are brief bursts of generalized delta waves as the patient falls asleep.
HR:  58 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Low voltage, generalized background theta.
Brief bursts of FIRDA.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The observed EEG pattern is non-specific but most consistent with a metabolic/toxic pattern.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Low voltage, generalized background theta. Brief bursts of FIRDA.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 45-year-old, uncooperative male with a witnessed tonic-clonic seizure, postictal confusion, agitation, and possible withdrawal symptoms.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Librium, Haldol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake record in a patient who becomes cooperative over the course of the study.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is low voltage, well organized with a symmetric, reactive posterior rhythm of approximately 10 Hz.  There is generous background beta activity.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the posterior dominant rhythm with an increase in beta activity.
HR:  116 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The beta activity described above may be due to this patient’s medications.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing in the lab with sleep and hyperventilation could be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is an 56-year-old gentleman with a hip fracture, alcohol abuse, epilepsy, and a DVT.  The patient had three seizures on 2/5/03.  He requires restraints for self-induced picking at his skin.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Topamax, antibiotics, many others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is diffusely slow and poorly organized with a low voltage delta and theta frequency activity. This pattern is seen when the patient is awake or stuporous.  The patient is observed by a nurse and tech and there is IV or other drip.  There was an unusual, somewhat periodic complex identified in the background with an unusual field of spread and phase reversal.  In specific montages including a referential ear montage, the activity is clearly maximum on the right but with spread to the left and in some montages which accentuate P4, it is possible to identify a P4 phase reversal.  The activity is usually unilateral but sometimes bilateral and sometimes seems to be asynchronous on the other side.  Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in faster frequency activity, as well as brief arousals.
The unusual, periodic activity in this record can be clearly differentiated from EKG artifact and there is no identifiable other source of artifact for this individual.
HR:  104 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Periodic activity poorly localized but probably maximum in the right parietal region, although sometimes generalized.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing differs from previous studies and suggests a process in the parietal regions, which may be epileptiform in nature.  No seizures were recorded.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing. Periodic activity poorly localized but probably maximum in the right parietal region, although sometimes generalized.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is an 8-year-old male with hydrocephalus following bacterial meningitis with an episode of one-minute loss of consciousness.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the Pediatric Unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is awake in a supported wheelchair. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the child is awake.  The background EEG demonstrates a relatively low voltage, theta and/or delta pattern in the frontocentral regions.  From the occipital regions, there is somewhat irregular 2 to 4 Hz activity, which is high amplitude. Sometimes with this activity, there is an occipital sharp wave. In addition, in wakefulness, there is a central, high amplitude spike and slow wave complex which is maximum at C3/CZ. This has a relatively generous field of spread, but in appropriate montages it clearly seems to be maximum from the left.  Despite the shunt, there is no significant breech on the right.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a child of this age due to:
Nearly continuous occipitally predominant delta activity with right greater than left occipital sharp and slow wave complexes or spike and slow wave complexes.
High amplitude left central or midline spike and slow wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a bihemispheric process effecting both gray and white matter. In addition, epileptiform activity was seen in more than one region, but supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy if this child’s behaviors are thought to be seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a child of this age due to Nearly continuous occipitally predominant delta activity with right greater than left occipital sharp and slow wave complexes or spike and slow wave complexes. High amplitude left central or midline spike and slow wave activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 9-year-old, right-handed male with staring spells, attention deficit disorder, mild cerebral palsy, developmental delay with delayed walking at age three.  Breach delivery, anxiety, hyperactivity, and asthma.
MEDICATIONS: Celexa.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age with a 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with 50 to 70 V and age-appropriate quantities of background theta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record producing an increase in theta with one or two shifting asymmetries but no definite lateralization.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in amplitude of the alpha rhythm with an increase in background theta.  Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
Photic stimulation elicits driving at 5 Hz and faster flash frequencies.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG is within the range of normal for a child of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record and no significant lateralizing features were seen. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing may be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG is within the range of normal for a child of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 3.1-year-old male with a history of syncope, cyanosis treated with ice.  More than one episode of loss of consciousness.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the Pediatric Unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the child is awake. In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age with an 8.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm reaching 100 V and some posterior slow waves of youth.  An attempt is made with hyperventilation and there is some background slowing identified with hyperventilation, although the full three minutes could not be completed.  LAMBDA was seen in portions of the record.  Very brief drowsiness is characterized by a small amount of background slowing.
HR:  132 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG for a child of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The normal developmental milestones have been achieved.  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy and clinical correlation is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG for a child of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 41-year-old male with seizures since age five, last seizure in September.  History of febrile convulsions, possibly treated with Lithium.
MEDICATIONS: Allegra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10.5 Hz, 30 V posterior dominant rhythm and a modest amount of  low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm with vertex waves identified in stage I sleep.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.
Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving.  Hyperventilation produces a small increase in the background theta.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. Comparison with previous records may be of use to evaluate epileptiform activity.  Alternatively, an additional recording could be helpful to further delineate epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is an 83-year-old woman with right-sided weakness, confusion, aphasia, found with a bruise over the eye, extended her stroke this morning.
MEDICATIONS: Labetalol, insulin, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is awake and apprehensive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Much of the EEG is obscured by the patient’s muscle artifact.  She is biting or grinding her jaw throughout much of the record. Interpretable portions of the record show a pattern, which appears to be relatively symmetric with a mixture of rhythmic theta and delta activity, with a primary frequency of rhythmic theta.  There are no significant asymmetries, although the muscle artifact may obscure such.
HR:  116 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Because of the muscle artifact described above, a follow-up study when the patient is a bit calmer may be helpful to identify underlying focal features.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-year-old male with MVA, multiple injuries, head injury requiring treatment with Dilantin.  Admitted with right flank pain, fever, rash, and acute renal failure.
MEDICATIONS: Percocet, Dilaudid, Tylenol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is primarily a drowsy record. Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is symmetric. The vast majority of the record is drowsiness with rhythmic background theta.  Symmetric vertex waves are identified in stage I sleep.
Brief awake state is characterized by an 8.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Photic stimulation does not significantly activate the record.
HR:  88 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG at the limits of normal primarily in drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The excessive drowsiness may be due to this patient’s medications.  A follow-up EEG in the lab when the patient is more alert may be helpful in determining whether or not there is an underlying epileptic focus in this individual with head trauma.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG at the limits of normal primarily in drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 37-year-old woman with a gunshot wound to the head in 1992, HIV, epilepsy, recently diagnosed with meningitis 3/29/03, cocaine dependency and recurrent seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Ceftriaxone, Haldol, Heparin, Ativan, Dilantin, many others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is noted to have a craniotomy defect in the right.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is awake.  The background EEG is poorly organized and there is a prominent craniotomy defect with a breech rhythm from the right hemisphere.  A somewhat irregular posterior dominant rhythm ranging from 6.5 to 7.5 Hz is identified and 50 to 70 V in amplitude. In addition, there is arrhythmic delta activity from the right posterior quadrant.
HR:  104 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing with poor organization.
Focal slowing from the right posterior quadrant and right hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definite epileptiform activity was identified and no seizures were recorded.  This tracing supports a diffuse disorder of cerebral function, as well as a structural abnormality in the right hemisphere.  No previous EEGs were available for comparison.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing with poor organization. Focal slowing from the right posterior quadrant and right hemisphere.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 52-year-old female with an unknown past medical history with acute renal failure, rhabdomyolysis, seizure, and negative CAT scan.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Ativan, and antibiotics.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is intubated and poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is continuous, low voltage and includes low voltage diffuse rhythmic theta and delta.  The primary frequencies in the background are 3 to 5 Hz, but there is some faster and some slower frequency activity.  Stimulation of the patient produces some rhythmic artifact, as well as attenuation of the EEG, but no clear arousal. In the initial portions of the record, there is little variability in the record, however, as the recording continues, there is an increase in  beta frequency activity, as well as some evidence of spontaneous variability and reactivity.
HR:  102 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: With the poor reactivity and variability identified in the initial portions of the record but an improvement towards the close of the record, a dynamic process such as a metabolic or toxic encephalopathy or even postictal state may contribute to this pattern. No epileptiform features were seen and no seizures were recorded.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Generalized background slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 20-year-old male found unresponsive with a blood alcohol level of 375.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz, 40 V posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Occasional posterior slow waves of youth are identified, as is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, increasing the amplitude of the background.  Immediately after HV, the patient becomes somewhat drowsy with slow rolling eye movements followed by attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in background theta.  Vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are seen in stage II sleep.
Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If clinically indicated, a repeat tracing capturing deeper stages of sleep could be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 76-year-old gentleman with hypoglycemic attack, left leg shaking, and chronic ischemic white matter disease seen on MRI.
MEDICATIONS: Coumadin, insulin, Lipitor, and Atenolol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record without hyperventilation or photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized for a subject of this age with a 9 Hz, 40 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements. Vertex waves are seen in stage I sleep. There are also some bursts of frontally predominant delta in the transition from wakefulness to sleep.
HR:  66 BPM, irregular.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness for a subject of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness for a subject of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 67-year-old gentleman who had missed dialysis and had a prolonged seizure in dialysis.  The patient received IV Dilantin and developed chorea movements immediately afterwards.  History of right cerebellar infarct.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is having continuous chorea form movements. These movements partly obscure the EEG.  There does not appear to be an underlying epileptiform correlate with the movements, however.  As the EEG continues, approximately six minutes into the EEG, the movements decrease and the EEG pattern is one of diffuse background slowing with poor organization and a mixture of rhythmic delta and theta frequency activity.  There are occasional shifting asymmetries and occasionally there is higher amplitude frontally predominant delta in one hemisphere or the other.
As the recording continues and the patient is moving less, there is an area of focal delta identified from the left occipital/posterior temporal region.
HR:  104 BPM, irregular.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing and poor organization.
Occasional focal slowing identified at the close of the record characterized by a left occipital temporal delta.
Choreiform movements without EEG change.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: As discussed with the clinical team, the chorea form movements may be an adverse effect of Phenytoin infusion and did not appear to be seizures.  A follow-up EEG may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing and poor organization. Occasional focal slowing identified at the close of the record characterized by a left occipital temporal delta. Choreiform movements without EEG change.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 56-year-old male with carotid stenosis.
MEDICATIONS: None listed.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was deferred, but photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a symmetric, reactive 10.5 Hz, 60 V posterior dominant rhythm.  Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm with slow rolling eye movements. Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.  Photic stimulation elicits driving at intermediate flash frequencies.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and stage I sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and stage I sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 57-year-old male with alcohol withdrawal seizures, chronic cerebrovascular disease, and pneumonia.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Hydralazine, Labetalol, Catapres, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. It was felt that the patient was hyperventilating throughout the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the EEG begins, the patient is awake in a noisy bedside environment with a number of background conversations that appear not to be related to him or his care.  He is markedly tachypneic. The background EEG demonstrates an awake pattern with an 8.5 Hz, 30 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm in a background with generous amounts of beta activity.  There is a fair amount of movement artifact, but there is no definite background slowing. Photic stimulation elicits driving at intermediate and faster flash frequencies.
HR:  140 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The clinical team was contacted regarding the tachypnea and tachycardia.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 77-year-old male with a UTI, metabolic encephalopathy, DNR, left MCA infarct, and seizure on 5/17/03.
MEDICATIONS: Multiple antibiotics, Ativan.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is described as intubated and “tense.”
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is markedly abnormal. Portions of the record show dramatic suppression from the left in an overall low voltage pattern.  The frequencies from the right include delta and theta frequency activity and there are rare right temporal sharp waves identified in the background.  While some portions of the record are partly compromised by a 60 Hz artifact, as the recording continues, the overall pattern remains extremely low voltage.  Stimulation of the patient does not produce a change in the background. Of note, at the close of the record, the EEG is approximately at baseline in terms of the very low voltage pattern with a degree of suppression seen from each hemisphere.
HR:  __ BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Intermittent, sometimes marked suppression from the left hemisphere.
Low voltage, generalized slow pattern from the right with occasional temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: To some extent, the dynamic features described above may be an artifact. Given the overall low voltage record and the challenges of recording in an ICU with the appearance of 60 Hz, some of the deterioration in the pattern may be an artifact. This tracing supports a severe disturbance of cerebral function effecting the left hemisphere more than the right, as well as potentially a partial mechanism for seizures on the right.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Intermittent, sometimes marked suppression from the left hemisphere. Low voltage, generalized slow pattern from the right with occasional temporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 65-year-old male with Dilantin toxicity, multi-infarct dementia, alcohol abuse, and lead poisoning.
MEDICATIONS: Lipitor, Zonisamide, Paxil, Dilantin, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is somnolent with nonsensical speech.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is diffusely slow.  There is shifting asymmetries and some portions of the record demonstrate relative suppression on the right compared to the left. The overall background is one of theta frequency activity with occasional delta and occasional faster frequency activity.  There is no well-defined posterior dominant rhythm in apparent wakefulness.  There is a discrete sharp and slow complex identified in the left central parietal region, seen particularly in drowsiness.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Intermittent suppression from the right.
Left central parietal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No seizures were recorded.  This EEG supports a diffuse disorder of cerebral function effecting both gray and white matter, which may include toxic and/or metabolic encephalopathy or postictal state.  A partial mechanism for epilepsy can be considered.  Correlation with imaging is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing. Intermittent suppression from the right. Left central parietal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 14-year-old male with multiple craniospinal surgeries, learning disabled with breakthrough seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Valproate, Lamotrigine, Dopamine, and sedative hypnotics.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The child is intubated and has a previous craniotomy scar.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is abnormal and is at times discontinuous.  The overall pattern is one of delta with occasional bursts of frontally predominant fast activity including a mixture of beta, as well as sharply contoured theta frequency activity.  The record is intermittently discontinuous.  There is an amplitude asymmetry with higher amplitude fast activity on the right.  There are occasional bursts of sharply contoured delta activity from the right temporal region.  Stimulation of the patient is associated with less in the way of discontinuity, but not a significant alerting response.
HR:  104 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing with a discontinuous pattern.
Intermittent bursts of fast activity, higher amplitude on the right compared to the left.
Occasional sharply contoured delta from the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a severe, diffuse disorder of cerebral function effecting both hemispheres, perhaps the right more than the left.  Because of the intermittent discontinuity and the history of sedation, the possibility of either administration of anesthetic doses of sedatives, hypnotic medications, or a severe disorder of cerebral function could be considered. No seizures were recorded.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing with a discontinuous pattern. Intermittent bursts of fast activity, higher amplitude on the right compared to the left. Occasional sharply contoured delta from the right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 27-year-old male with a history of head trauma with right temporal lobe fracture.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Tylenol, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record with photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: When the patient is maximally awake, the background EEG is acceptably organized for an adult of this age with an 8.5 Hz alpha rhythm.  Early in drowsiness, there are bursts of theta activity and the record becomes slightly disorganized. There is also an increase in beta frequency in drowsiness.  Vertex waves are identified in stage __ sleep.  In addition, in the transition to drowsiness, there are bursts of frontally predominant slowing.  The patient seems to be drowsy, intermittently demonstrating bursts of frontally predominant slowing followed by arousal.
Photic stimulation produces brief driving at intermediate flash frequencies.
HR:  70 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and early sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  This EEG is within normal limits for a subject of this age. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat tracing may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and early sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 59-year-old woman with PBD, DM, COPD, OSA, gangrene, sepsis, requiring tracheostomy due to respiratory failure with confusion, psychomotor slowing, and difficulty moving her extremities.
MEDICATIONS: Insulin, Vancomycin, and multiple antibiotics.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is described as obtunded, lethargic, or asleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: When the patient is resting quietly, the background is very low voltage with low voltage theta frequency activity of 5 to 7 Hz, which sometimes is more prominent in the anterior regions, and low amplitude 0.5 to 3 Hz delta activity which sometimes demonstrates shifting asymmetries. Stimulation of the patient produces an alerting response clinically with eye opening on each occasion, but on some occasions there is a better defined arousal pattern with a 6 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.
HR:  108 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Shifting arrhythmic delta activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  These features are non-specific but support a diffuse disorder of cerebral function effecting both gray and white matter.  This may be due to a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy, diffuse CNS injury, or chronic underlying cerebral disturbance. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow-up study may be of use.  There were non-specific hallmarks of a metabolic encephalopathy such as triphasic waves, and the presence of reactivity and variability is a positive prognostic finding.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing. Shifting arrhythmic delta activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 74-year-old woman with dementia and abnormal MRI. She also had recurrent loss of consciousness and sphenoid/orbital abnormality on MRI.
MEDICATIONS: Heparin, Metoprolol, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record. The tech has some problems with the T2 electrode.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is low voltage.  There is a low voltage, posterior dominant rhythm identified of approximately 9.5 Hz, with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by symmetric background theta, attenuation of the alpha, and an increase in background beta. In the transition to and from stage I sleep, there are rare occasional bursts of shifting asymmetries.  The patient is noted to have some eye movement in sleep.  POSTS, vertex waves, and K complexes are seen in stage II sleep.
HR:  82 BPM, slightly irregular.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for a subject of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definite focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are an important consideration, a repeat tracing could be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for a subject of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 56-year-old male found unresponsive at home with rising temperature, CPK, and multiple metabolic abnormalities.
MEDICATIONS: Ceftriaxone, Erythromycin, Fentanyl, and Versed (these were stopped one hour prior to the EEG).
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is comatose and unresponsive. (intubated ?).  check tech sheet
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is medium to low amplitude and is comprised of a pattern that is a mixture of rhythmic 4 to 6 Hz theta frequency activity, which occurs in bursts with slower underlying low voltage delta activity in a somewhat discontinuous or paroxysmal pattern. The theta activity is most prominent in the frontal regions where it is sometimes higher amplitude and more sharply contoured and may reach a frequency of 7 to 8 Hz, with a 7 to 8 Hz discharge among the theta frequency activity.  Stimulation of the patient does not significantly activate the record.
HR:  142 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background with a pattern of rhythmic theta, smaller amounts of delta, and subtle discontinuity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These features are non-specific, but support a diffuse disorder of cerebral function.  The pattern would be typical of that of pharmacologic coma. No definite focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record. If additional information is required, a repeat tracing after this patient’s sedative, hypnotic medications have worn off may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Replacement of normal background with a pattern of rhythmic theta, smaller amounts of delta, and subtle discontinuity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 53-year-old woman with an episode of aphasia, a right central facial, and a question of a tumor versus stroke identified on MRI.
MEDICATIONS: Coumadin, Digoxin, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the or at the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is low voltage and rich in beta frequency activity.  There is a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm identified from the right occipital region.  The primary pattern is a drowsy pattern, but in drowsiness there is sharply contoured theta frequency activity maximum at F7.  In addition, there seems to be a slight variability and at times there is a bit more theta frequency in the right frontal region compared to the left, although the central regions are symmetric.  As the patient continues in a relatively drowsy state, there is persistent rhythmic theta identified from the left frontotemporal region with left frontal sharp and slow wave complexes.  These are discrete and are best identified with a sensitivity of 5.  They can be identified both in the montages which accentuate temporal abnormalities, as well as referential montages. Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
HR:  98 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness due to:
Subtle focal slowing from the left anterior temporal region with associated discrete sharp waves and sharply contoured delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a structural abnormality in the left frontotemporal region and raises the possibility of a partial mechanism for seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness due to Subtle focal slowing from the left anterior temporal region with associated discrete sharp waves and sharply contoured delta.

report:

MEDICATIONS: Lamictal and Depakote.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered within normal limits.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 56-year-old gentleman with a history of astrocytoma, seizure disorder with multiple surgical interventions and shunt.  The last one was May 5, 2003.  The patient was found to have possible Jacksonian-March syndrome seizures
MEDICATIONS: Steroids, low ADD ______________.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was not performed, but photic stimulation was completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is poorly organized and diffusely slow. It is intermixed with theta and delta activity.  A breach rhythm was identified in the left hemisphere.  Frequent, focal sharply contoured delta activity was found at T2 and T4.  Photic stimulation elicited driving as well as occasional, left occipital sharp waves. No  seizure activity was identified on the video recording.
HR: 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Diffuse slowing.
Poorly organized background.
Breach rhythm in the left hemisphere.
Focal sharp delta activity in the right anterior temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG recording demonstrates cerebral dysfunction of both hemispheres.  The breach rhythm reflects a skull defect.  No seizures were identified in the record, but potential or epileptiform activity was seen in both hemispheres.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Diffuse slowing. Poorly organized background. Breach rhythm in the left hemisphere. Focal sharp delta activity in the right anterior temporal region.

report:

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.

Frequent vertex waves, spindles, and K complexes were identified.  The patient was awakened by his snoring, but he rapidly went back to stage II sleep. report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 58-year-old female with CAD, diabetes, hypothyroidism, status-post CT surgery for MVA on June 6, now with obtundation.  The patient had multiple complications including infarction, carditis, bacteremia, respiratory failure, acute renal failure on continuous hemodialysis, and sepsis.
MEDICATIONS: Epinephrine and multiple antibiotics.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation and hyperventilation were not performed.  The patient is unresponsive during this recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is low voltage and diffusely slow with a mixture of arrhythmic theta and delta activity. Generous amounts of muscle artifact were superimposed.  Stimulation of the patient did not change the EEG.  No focal or epileptiform activity was seen.
HR: 80 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background with low voltage and diffuse slowing with a mixture of arrhythmic theta and delta activity.
Stimulation of the patient caused no reactivity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG tracing demonstrates a severe disturbance of cerebral function.  This pattern may be seen in patients with metabolic or toxic encephalopathy or a postictal pattern, however, no localization or epileptiform activity was identified.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Replacement of normal background with low voltage and diffuse slowing with a mixture of arrhythmic theta and delta activity. Stimulation of the patient caused no reactivity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 58-year-old male status-post MVA, PEA, cardiac arrest, now intubated and unresponsive with myoclonus. Past medical history significant for schizophrenia.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan and Valproate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is noted to have left arm twitching on one occasion.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is in a burst suppression pattern.  Numbers of high amplitude, sharply contoured theta and faster frequency activity are identified relatively symmetrically from the frontal regions.  The suppression in the background is quite variable ranging with as many as one to three second bursts in 15 seconds to last. There are also portions where it attenuates rather than actually suppresses.  There is variability and in some portions, the right hemisphere is much more suppressed and is flatter longer than the left.  In other portions of the record, there may be a bit more theta on either the left or the right.
Stimulation of the patient does not significantly activate the record.  Jerking movements are difficult to identify in this video.  There is no clear change with the jerking during the EEG given the overall variability in the pattern described above.
HR:  __ BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Burst suppression pattern.
Intermittent shifting asymmetries sometimes with more significant suppression on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a severe disorder of cerebral function effecting both hemispheres.  There is evidence in this record to suggest that the right hemisphere may be more effected than the left.  In the absence of hypothermia or very high dose sedative hypnotic drugs, this tracing would be most supportive of a severe anoxic encephalopathy, although this may also represent a traumatic pattern.  The prognosis for this pattern is considered poor if durations of time since the cardiac arrest is greater than 24 hours.  Of note, on the few occasions that the patient did experience jerking, there was clear muscle artifact in the EEG suggesting that subtle twitching wasn’t a major clinical factor.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Burst suppression pattern. Intermittent shifting asymmetries sometimes with more significant suppression on the right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 71-year-old male admitted for pancreatitis and change in mental status.  History of check tech sheet___ secondary to gastritis, ARF, hypertension, hepatitis C, cerebral aneurysm clip over 30 years ago with left temporal skull defect.
MEDICATIONS: Protonix, insulin, Heparin, antibiotics, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Portable digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This is an awake through drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates intra-hemispheric asymmetry and diffuse slowing.  The alpha rhythm is slow with 6 to 7 Hz, 20 V activity in maximal wakefulness.  There is continuous left hemispheric rhythmic delta activity of 90 V and left temporal breech activity is seen.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements and decreased amplitude of the background.  Occasionally, sharp activity was seen in the T3 region in drowsiness. Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Interhemispheric asymmetry with a breech rhythm in the left hemisphere.
Diffuse slowing.
Occasional left mid-temporal sharp activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing demonstrates a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function, is a non-specific finding but may be seen in metabolic encephalopathy or due to medication.  The intrahemispheric asymmetry with the left breach rhythm is suggestive of a skull defect and structural lesion.  The left temporal sharp activity suggests focal mechanism of epilepsy in this patient.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Interhemispheric asymmetry with a breech rhythm in the left hemisphere. Diffuse slowing. Occasional left mid-temporal sharp activity.

report:

MEDICATIONS: Ceftriaxone, Acyclovir, Vancomycin, and insulin.

Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in some faster theta frequency activity of approximately 7 Hz, as well as some beta frequency activity.  Occasional vertex waves are seen in sleep.

1.	Symmetric generalized background slowing.

There were no periodic complexes in the temporal regions as may be seen in herpes infection, and there were no specific characteristics of a metabolic encephalopathy.  The features described above are non-specific.  If herpes encephalitis is an important consideration, a follow-up study may be of use as these features are not always seen acutely.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Symmetric generalized background slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 48-year-old woman with syncope versus seizures with chest pain.
MEDICATIONS: ?
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the ER using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is drowsy.  The background EEG is primarily theta.  There is some temporal wicket activity.  There are intermittent bursts of sharply contoured irregular, higher amplitude theta frequency activity with bursts typically lasting under three seconds in duration.  Most of them last under one second.  Some of these have an underlying spike and slow wave complex seen in association with them.  In addition, unfortunately this is also the region where the patient has EKG artifact and an irregular heart rate.  The bursts of irregular temporal theta have a left mid-to-anterior temporal underlying spike and slow wave or sharp and slow wave complex.  On occasion, that epileptiform activity isn’t seen in the posterior rather than the anterior temporal region.  In addition, there is a bilateral distribution of the regular theta.

HR:  96 BPM, irregular.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Irregular, sharply contoured bursts of theta activity with an underlying sharp wave from the left temporal region with variable maximum and occasional bitemporal involvement.
Generalized background slowing.
Irregular heart rate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The irregular heart rate or the epileptiform activity could account for this patient’s loss of consciousness and clinical correlation may be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Irregular, sharply contoured bursts of theta activity with an underlying sharp wave from the left temporal region with variable maximum and occasional bitemporal involvement. Generalized background slowing. Irregular heart rate.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 59-year-old male with a history of seizures and epilepsy onset since his teenage years. Last seizure was several weeks ago.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Dilantin, and Phenobarbital.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the Long-Term EEG Monitoring unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is disorganized and diffusely slow. There is 6 to 7 Hz, 40 to 60 V posterior dominant alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Occasional left temporal sharp activity with focal slowing is observed.  In random sleepiness, during the night sleep stage, left temporal sharp activity was dramatically increased.  Occasional spikes, as well as rare right temporal sharp activity was also observed.    During deeper sleep stages, occasional left sharp activity and rare right temporal sharp activity can be seen.  Sleep is characterized by vertex waves, spindles, and K complexes.  Deeper sleep stages reveal synchronized delta activity with high amplitudes more than 75 V occupying half or more than half of the epoch.
EVENTS:  No seizure events were reported, and no push button events occurred over this long-term EEG monitoring.
HR:  56 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Frequent, left temporal sharp activity with focal slowing.
Occasional right temporal sharp activity.
Long-Term Monitoring, 10/14/03 at 06:34 to 10/15/03 at 01:14

CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 59-year-old male with a history of seizures and epilepsy onset since his teenage years. Last seizure was several weeks ago.

report:

Sleeping is characterized by vertex waves.  Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.  Photic stimulation did not activate the record.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 58-year-old male on an LVAD device with hemorrhagic complications, noted to have intermittent left motor asymmetry and intracerebral hemorrhage on CT scan.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, morphine, Haldol, Fentanyl and many others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is sedated.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The initial portions of the record are low voltage beta with superimposed significant muscle activity.  As the recording continues, the patient becomes less tense and a low voltage beta pattern is identified with symmetric underlying low voltage delta.  Stimulation of the patient clearly produces an alerting with an increase in muscle, as well as the brief appearance of some alpha frequency activity.  There is variability in the record and there are portions of the record where there is lower voltage symmetric theta and delta.  The tech notes that the patient occasionally tenses his hands or bites on his endotracheal tube, again producing an increase in muscle and beta activity.  In later portions of the record, as the patient appears to relax, there is lower voltage, slow delta seen.
HR:  102 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background with beta frequency pattern.
Generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Some of the features described above are compatible with a pharmacologic coma.  The spontaneous reactivity and variability are positive prognostic signs even in the setting of sedation.  With relaxation, we see a diffuse pattern of delta supporting a diffuse disorder of cerebral function and contributing factors may include the CNS processes described above or the medications.  No focal features and no epileptiform features were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Replacement of normal background with beta frequency pattern. Generalized background slowing.

report:
