report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 91-year-old woman admitted with a history of dementia, advanced AlzheimerÕs disease, now with myoclonic jerks.

MEDICATIONS: Antibiotics, morphine, and others.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is diffusely slow and disorganized with rhythmic slowing of 4 to 5 Hz. Normal posterior alpha rhythm is not seen.  A small amount of low voltage beta activity is seen in the frontal and central regions.  Occasionally, writhing and jerky movements were seen on the digital video camera, but no EEG changes were recorded.  One sharp wave was seen at T3 and another seen in the occipital area linked to the writhing or jerky-like short movements.  Drowsiness is characterized by vertex waves.  Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.

HR:  96 BPM.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Disorganized background with diffuse slowing.
2. Single sharp activity seen in the left temporal area and another sharp wave seen in the occipital region.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing demonstrates an diffuse slowing, which is non-specific.  The generalized diffuse slowing in the disorganized background is consistent with cerebral dysfunction such as AlzheimerÕs disease, dementing illnesses or other forms of encephalopathy.  The sharp waves can also be seen in patients with AlzheimerÕs disease or dementia.   Multiple writhing movements were observed on the video camera, but with no EEG correlate. The jerks were associated with focal spikes on 2 occasions.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Disorganized background with diffuse slowing. 2. Single sharp activity seen in the left temporal area and another sharp wave seen in the occipital region.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 55-year-old male with post-traumatic epilepsy, subsequent stroke, now with breakthrough seizures.  Patient confused for a prolonged period of time afterwards.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, aspirin, and other medications.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is awake and cooperative throughout the record.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive.  There is subtle, intermittent focal slowing identified from the left frontal temporal region.  At times this includes rhythmic activity of 3 to 5 Hz.  On other occasions, there seems to be intermittent disruption of faster frequency activity in this region.  In relaxed wakefulness and early drowsiness, there are occasional sharp waves identified maximum at FP1 or occasionally isoelectric at FP1/F3.  On occasion, these may be maximum in the left anterior temporal electrode.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and subtly accentuates some of the focal slowing in the frontotemporal/frontocentral regions.
Photic stimulation elicits a driving response at 15 Hz, but the left anterior temporal sharp waves seem to be accentuated by lower frequency stimulation.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Left anterior temporal sharp waves with some variability; some of the epileptiform discharges are maximum in the left frontal region.
Intermittent focal slowing from the left, accentuated by hyperventilation.
?Accentuated focal epileptiform activity seen in photic stimulation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These features are similar to a previous study dated 5/17/02.  When the epileptiform activity is more prominent in this record, photic stimulation also appeared to accentuate this pattern.  This may be due to the proximity of this recording to this patient’s postictal state.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Left anterior temporal sharp waves with some variability; some of the epileptiform discharges are maximum in the left frontal region. Intermittent focal slowing from the left, accentuated by hyperventilation. ?Accentuated focal epileptiform activity seen in photic stimulation.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 4-year-old female with cerebral palsy, epilepsy, born at 42 weeks, but with a perinatal stroke.
MEDICATIONS: Phenobarbital.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The child is described as crying.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: This is an extremely challenging EEG due to muscle and motion artifact, however, in the interpretable portions of the record, the background is diffusely slow with a mixture of beta and theta frequency activity.  The anticipated developmental milestones for a child of this age are not well defined.  There are brief portions of the record when the child awakens with spontaneous eye opening and eye closure.  At this time, there is a suggestion of a 6 Hz posterior dominant rhythm in a background with rhythmic 3 to 4 Hz activity.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is hypersynchronous, high amplitude, frontally predominant delta activity, as well as some rhythmic slowing from the left.  In the brief portions of the record without movement artifact, there appears to be an underlying sharp and slow wave or spike and slow wave focus from the posterior regions.
HR:  140 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a child of this age due to:
Absence of some of the developmental milestones, as well as appropriate developmental organization.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Because of the amount of artifact, no other inferences should be made from this EEG.  There appears to be underlying epileptiform activity from the right as well as asynchronicity as the child drifts off to sleep.  If further characterization of this child’s epilepsy is important, a repeat, sedated study may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a child of this age due to Absence of some of the developmental milestones, as well as appropriate developmental organization.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 36-year-old male found unconscious with incontinence, overdose on cocaine and benzodiazepines.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz, 30 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm, sometimes with slowing of the alpha, followed by an increase in background beta.  Vertex waves, K complexes, POSTS, and spindles are seen in stage II sleep, again with abundant beta frequency activity throughout.  In wakefulness, occasional LAMBDA is seen.
Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving.
HR:  __ BPM. See prelim sheet
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness throughout stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The generous beta may be due to this patient’s benzodiazepine ingestion.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness throughout stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 20-year-old male with hypertension and acute lupus with acute renal failure awaiting transplant with recurrent seizures yesterday.  History of renal and hepatic insufficiency.

MEDICATIONS: Multiple antibiotics, Dilantin, Kayexalate(?), and many others. Check spelling

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is awake and described as irritable.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is abnormal. Much of the waking background is low voltage beta with intermittent bursts of rhythmic, frontally predominant delta.  There are other portions of the record in apparent wakefulness where there is more significant background theta.  There are occasional bursts of shifting arrhythmic delta activity noted as well.  While there is no definite epileptiform activity, there are one or two bursts of sharply contoured activity in the right frontal region.

Drowsiness is characterized by a decrease in movement artifact and an increase in frontally predominant, rhythmic high amplitude delta.

HR:  90 BPM.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing
2. FIRDA.
3. Occasional shifting slowing with some suggestion of sharply contoured slowing on the right.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These features are non-specific but support a diffuse disorder of cerebral function affecting both gray and white matter.  Consideration for a toxic and/or metabolic encephalopathy would be appropriate in this case. No definite epileptiform features were seen.  Comparison with previous EEGs may be helpful.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Generalized background slowing
2. FIRDA. 3. Occasional shifting slowing with some suggestion of sharply contoured slowing on the right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 57-year-old woman with multiple medical problems: CHF, hypertension, CAD, MI, diabetes, seizures, COPD, asthma, DVT, and a tracheostomy in 2002.  Patient was initially admitted with shortness of breath at 1:30 AM today and found to have a change in mental status and coded. Throughout the CPR, her oxygen saturation was in the 90s.  A CT scan showed old, right frontal and parietal strokes and a new right occipital stroke.

MEDICATIONS: Morphine, Dilantin, and antibiotics.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is diffusely slow and disorganized.   There is a 6 to 7 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a moderate amount of generalized beta activity. Occasionally, shifting asymmetries are seen in the background with theta as well as arrhythmic delta activity.  Sleeping is evidenced by a few vertex waves. Deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.

HR:  72 BPM.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Diffusely slow and disorganized background.
2. Shifting asymmetric and rhythmic theta with arrhythmic delta.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The patient is not in coma or status epilepticus- she is awake which is a positive prognostic feature after cardiac arrest.  This tracing is suggestive of a diffuse pathological process involving both gray and white matter.  Prior CVAs or todayÕs events may produce this pattern.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Diffusely slow and disorganized background. 2. Shifting asymmetric and rhythmic theta with arrhythmic delta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 29-year-old male with epilepsy since birth, multiple shunt revisions, headaches, seizures, depression, anxiety, and substance abuse. Seizures characterized by seeing spots and colors, left-handed arm shaking, and other symptoms.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is diffusely slow and somewhat poorly organized.  There is generous rhythmic background theta and occasional shifting arrhythmic delta activity.  At times a posterior dominant rhythm of 9 Hz can be identified.  Some portions of the record demonstrate an asymmetry with a bit higher amplitude arrhythmic theta from the left temporal region compared to the right.  There also appears to be a breach rhythm in the left frontotemporal region with higher amplitude beta frequency activity in that region.  There are bursts of sharply contoured slowing with suspicious underlying sharp waves in the left frontocentral region in sleep.
Hyperventilation produces an increase in background slowing.  Photic stimulation does not significantly activate the record.  At the close of the record, in maximal wakefulness, the breach rhythm from the left frontocentral region is a bit more prominent and there are a handful of discrete left central sharp waves seen in wakefulness.
HR:  __ BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Excess background theta.
Background disorganization.
Focal slowing and occasional sharp waves identified on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No previous EEGs were available for comparison.  This tracing supports a process affecting both hemispheres as well as a partial mechanism for this patient’s epilepsy.  Of note, he reports left hand shaking and the sharp waves were seen on the left.  This may be due to false localization of the epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Excess background theta. Background disorganization. Focal slowing and occasional sharp waves identified on the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 90-year-old woman with encephalopathy and dementia.
MEDICATIONS: Zestril and Imdur.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is agitated and inappropriate throughout the study.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: With the patient resting comfortably, the background is markedly slow with a mixture of delta and theta.  There are asymmetries with some slower, arrhythmic delta seen on occasion on the left.  There is a significant amount of spontaneous variability and other portions of the record are richer in theta frequency activity.  Stimulation of the patient produces an alerting response with an increase in the rhythmic theta.
HR:  50 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Significant, generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In an individual who is agitated with this degree of slowing, consideration for either a delirium or an underlying dementia would be appropriate.  No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The intermittent focal slowing is of unclear clinical significance in this context.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Significant, generalized background slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 37-year-old male with a left temporal and occipital hemorrhage.

MEDICATIONS:  Haldol, thiamine folic acid, and antibiotics.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is intubated and sedated with Versed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is asymmetric and low voltage.  The normal posterior alpha rhythm is barely seen.  There is diffuse beta activity.  There is a nearly continuous left frontal and central slowing with polymorphic and arrhythmic delta activity.  Fast activity on the left anterior was also observed.  Stimulation of the patient did not cause variability.

HR:  114 BPM.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Asymmetric, disorganized and low voltage background.
2. Diffuse beta activity.
3. Focal slowing of polymorphic and arrhythmic delta activity in the left frontal and central areas.
4. Fast activity in the left anterior region.
5. Lack of variability with stimulation.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing demonstrates a severe cerebral dysfunction involving both gray and white matter.  The polymorphic slowing in the left frontal central region is suggestive of an underlying pathological process in this patient.  The diffuse beta activity together with fast activity in the left anterior region, as well as the absence of variability with stimulation, may be secondary to medications such as a pharmacological coma or patient in coma secondary to a structural lesion in the brain involving the reticular formation.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  When the patient is more stabilized or weaned off sedative medications, a follow-up EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Asymmetric, disorganized and low voltage background. 2. Diffuse beta activity. 3. Focal slowing of polymorphic and arrhythmic delta activity in the left frontal and central areas. 4. Fast activity in the left anterior region. 5. Lack of variability with stimulation.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is an 89-year-old woman admitted for change in mental status with acute encephalopathy, agitation, acute renal failure, afib, and small MI with small vessel disease.  This is a follow-up EEG tracing.
MEDICATIONS: Antibiotics and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed. The patient is intubated and ventilator dependent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is symmetric, continuous, and very low voltage with excessive beta activity.  A few 5 to 6 Hz delta activity is seen in the posterior region.  Stimulation of the patient caused spontaneous movement and increased the theta activity as well as scant amounts of delta activity.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Low voltage, diffusely slow background.
Excessive beta activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing is suggestive of a cerebral dysfunction involving both gray and white matter.  The excessive amount of beta activity may be due to medications such as benzodiazepine use.  The low voltage pattern may be due to the patient’s age and is considered normal for a patient of this advanced age.  In comparison to this patient’s previous EEG of February 19, 2004, as well as the presence of interaction caused by stimulation, this EEG is much improved.  No epileptiform discharges were seen in this tracing.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Low voltage, diffusely slow background. Excessive beta activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is an 89-year-old male admitted for intraventricular hemorrhage into the fourth ventricle and left parietal meningioma.
MEDICATIONS: Antihypertensives and Digoxin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This is an awake through light sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric and continuous with a lot of muscle artifact.  There is a 10 Hz, 25 V posterior dominant rhythm, which is well attenuated with eyes opened. There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Sleep mildly increases the theta and delta activity in the background.  Sleep is characterized by vertex waves, spindles, and a few K complexes.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and in sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Surprisingly, no focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and in sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 93-year-old male with an episode of tremulousness of the upper extremities and eyes rolling back in the head.  CT demonstrates generalized atrophy.
MEDICATIONS: Aspirin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and asleep record with photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG includes rhythmic 6 to 7 Hz theta activity.  There is a posterior dominant rhythm, which is more on the order of  5 to 6 Hz.  There is occasional, shifting, underlying arrhythmic delta activity. Brief stage I sleep is characterized by vertex waves followed by arousals.  Brief stage II sleep includes vertex waves and spindles.  Stimulation does not elicit a driving response.
HR:  60 BPM, irregular.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing with rhythmic slowing.
Occasional shifting arrhythmic delta activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG remains slow in the context of this patient’s age.  Consideration includes a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy as well as a chronic process including an underlying dementia. No epileptiform features were identified in this record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing with rhythmic slowing. Occasional shifting arrhythmic delta activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 70-year-old woman admitted with hallucinosis, right PCA and MCA infarcts with left hemiparesis, fluctuating mental status, and Alzheimer’s disease.
MEDICATIONS: Plavix and Nifedipine.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and briefly drowsy record in a patient with nearly continuous oral facial dyskinesias.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is nearly obscured by muscle, but underlying the muscle the activity appears to be of low voltage and relatively continuous.  As the patient drifts off to sleep, there is less in the way of background muscle and the EEG is a mixture of alpha and theta frequency activity.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is an intrahemispheric asymmetry apparent.  There is a posterior dominant rhythm identified of approximately 7 Hz on the left, but the faster frequency activity from the right hemisphere appears to be relatively attenuated.  As the patient becomes more responsive, again the oral facial dyskinesias and the prominent muscle activity obscure the EEG.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Modest background slowing.
Intrahemispheric asymmetry with disruption of faster frequency activity from the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a structural abnormality on the right involving gray matter, as well as at least a mild, diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Modest background slowing. Intrahemispheric asymmetry with disruption of faster frequency activity from the right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 68-year-old woman with an anoxic/hypoglycemic episode in the field, acute renal failure, prior left MCA stroke with chronic hemiparesis and aphasia, now persistently unresponsive.
MEDICATIONS: Valproate, Vancomycin, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is unresponsive with occasional eye movement or facial grimacing and unilateral deviation of the right eye (left eye prosthetic).
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  The activity from the left hemisphere is relatively suppressed with occasional left mid-to-posterior temporal sharp waves.  The right hemisphere demonstrates essentially a theta pattern.  There are occasional frontal sharp waves, left greater than right, some of which have a periodic nature to them.  Stimulation of the patient does not significantly active the record.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Intrahemispheric asymmetry, slower on the left than the right.
Left mid-temporal sharp waves.
Right frontal or bilateral periodic complexes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe, diffuse disorder of cerebral function.  Processes involving each hemisphere should be considered.  Correlation with follow-up neuroimaging may be helpful.  No seizures were recorded.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Intrahemispheric asymmetry, slower on the left than the right. Left mid-temporal sharp waves. Right frontal or bilateral periodic complexes.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 58-year-old woman with a history of syncope versus seizure 12/03/03, lower extremity weakness, and liver transplant in 1995.
MEDICATIONS: Prograf, Coumadin, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz, 40 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements and a more diffuse distribution of the beta frequency activity.  Abundant vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS are seen in stage II sleep.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing a small amount of background theta.  Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 79-year-old, right-handed male with a history of lung cancer, prolonged nearly two-month long hospitalization, PEG and trached with persistent drowsiness.
MEDICATIONS: Digoxin, Zoloft, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record. Towards the close of the record, the patient is alerted and stimulated.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG, when the patient is resting comfortably and is somewhat drowsy, is low voltage with a mixture of delta and theta.  With stimulation, the patient alerts.  The background EEG is primarily theta with smaller amounts of delta.  The overall background is somewhat obscured by muscle, but there is no significant asymmetry.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Excessive drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These features are non-specific but are characteristic of an underlying encephalopathy.  A toxic or metabolic cause as well as an underlying dementing process may all produce this pattern.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing. Excessive drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 63-year-old woman with change in mental status, multiple strokes, HTN, and CABG.
MEDICATIONS: Digoxin, Coumadin, Benadryl, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is mildly confused or drowsy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In apparent wakefulness, the background EEG is diffusely slow and disorganized. There is a hint of a 6 to 7 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and excess background theta.  There is shifting arrhythmic delta activity and generous beta activity in the frontocentral regions.
HR:  70 BPM, irregular.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Generalized background slowing and poor organization.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There were no significant focal or epileptiform features identified in this record.  The features described above are non-specific and may be seen in a chronic or acute disturbance of cerebral function.  There are no specific hallmarks of a metabolic encephalopathy although a metabolic encephalopathy may produce a similar pattern.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Generalized background slowing and poor organization.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 76-year-old male with left MCA seizure as well as multiple old seizures who presented with neurosyphilis, seizures, and PLEDS.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Topamax, and antibiotics.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates some marked intrahemispheric asymmetry.  The right hemisphere is modestly slow with a mixture of theta and smaller amounts of delta, but there is a well-defined and reactive posterior dominant rhythm.  The left hemisphere demonstrates primarily rhythmic theta with smaller amounts of delta, although at times a posterior dominant rhythm can be identified.  There are intermittent sharp waves identified from the left hemisphere.  These demonstrate variable maximum including left frontotemporal, anterior temporal, or frontal.  They range in amplitude from medium to high amplitude and are accompanied by generous after going slow waves.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing.  This is a dynamic record, and by the close of the record the activity from the right hemisphere is nearly normal and the left hemisphere is significantly less slow.
HR:  85 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Left frontal and temporal sharp waves.
Left hemispheric focal slowing.
Intermittent background slowing on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a focal mechanism for this patient’s seizures, as well as a structural or functional abnormality on the left involving both gray and white matter.  The dynamic pattern with improvement towards the close of the record may be part of a process in a patient who is overall improving.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Left frontal and temporal sharp waves. Left hemispheric focal slowing. Intermittent background slowing on the right.

report:

report:

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 71-year-old Spanish speaking male with epilepsy and memory disorder.
MEDICATIONS: Unknown.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The vast majority of the EEG demonstrates drowsiness or stage II sleep.  Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic theta, and in stage II sleep, symmetric vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are seen.
In wakefulness, the overall background is relatively low voltage with some muscle and a small amount of background theta. Unfortunately, there is a fair amount of artifact in the waking background.  Photic stimulation does not significantly activate the record.
HR:  __ BPM. Check tech sheet
IMPRESSION: This EEG is normal in sleep, but a question of generalized background slowing in wakefulness is seen.

report:
HISTORY: This is a 28-year-old woman with seizures since age 11.  She also has some unusual facial features.
MEDICATIONS: Paxil, Ranitidine, Seroquel, Lasix, Cozaar, and Albuterol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is symmetric and fairly well organized.  There is a 10 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant alpha rhythm, which is attenuated with eyes opened.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation increases the amplitude of the background.  Post-hyperventilation reveals pairs of sharp waves seen at F7 and T3-T5 area and then bursts of left temporal theta activity with T5 sharp and slow wave complexes.  Photic stimulation elicits driving.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Sharp activity observed in the left frontal and temporal areas.
Bursts of left temporal slowing with sharp and slow wave complexes in the left temporal area.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The focal features of epileptiform discharges in the left frontal and temporal areas indicates an underlying pathological process and supports a partial mechanism of epilepsy in this patient.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Sharp activity observed in the left frontal and temporal areas. Bursts of left temporal slowing with sharp and slow wave complexes in the left temporal area.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 4-year-old female with a seizure with associated fall down the stairs.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The child is asleep throughout much of the record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The majority of this record demonstrates stage II sleep, which on the whole is symmetric with symmetric vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  There are rare, shifting asymmetries.  The transition to slow wave sleep was characterized by bursts of rhythmic high amplitude slow delta.
HR:  120 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If there are questions regarding the maturational state of this child’s EEG, additional recording with wakefulness may be of use.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 4-year-old female with recurrent seizures, right-sided shaking of 15 minutes duration.  Positive family history.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is abnormal.  The primary frequency in the background is low voltage theta.  The interictal background is reasonably well organized for a child of this age with a 6 to 7 Hz posterior dominant rhythm of approximately 50 uV.  In wakefulness, this background is disrupted and an intermittent, 2.5 to 4 Hz spike and slow wave complex is seen primarily in the right occipital region.  This discharge is so prominent that there is some subtle focal slowing after the S/W.  There are also independent spike and slow wave complexes seen in the left frontocentral region (C3), but those with a classic spike and slow wave morphology are seen in the occipital region with some spread to other regions.  On occasion, they can also be seen at T5/T3 and once at P4.  Photic stimulation elicits driving, but doesn’t seem to augment these discharges.  Hyperventilation initially elicits bursts of rhythmic, frontally predominant slowing.  It doesn’t seem to elicit these interictal discharges which on one occasion are six seconds in duration.  There are bursts where the activity seems to come out of the left centrotemporal region and then 1.5 seconds later is followed by the occipital spike and slow wave activity.
HR:  116 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Frequent spike and slow wave activity seen in bursts or brief trains, primarily from the right occipital region, rarely generalized but occasionally seen in other localizations including the left frontocentral and left centrotemporal regions.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are after going slow waves, but little focal slowing outside of the epileptiform activity.  This EEG supports a multifocal process for this patient’s epilepsy,  however, it is possible that this EEG may also represent an unusual manifestation of a generalized or an inherited epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Frequent spike and slow wave activity seen in bursts or brief trains, primarily from the right occipital region, rarely generalized but occasionally seen in other localizations including the left frontocentral and left centrotemporal regions.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is an 11-year-old female with epilepsy since age 3; last seizure two years ago with shaking, drooling, and incontinence.  Positive family history of epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age with a 10 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Noted in wakefulness and increasing in drowsiness is a right central spike and slow wave complex with a large field of spread.  This ranges from discrete to a high amplitude complex and at times the field of spread varies from central parietal to frontocentral.  It may occur as couplets or a brief run of epileptiform activity and does appear to be associated with underlying focal slowing in the central parietal region.  Photic stimulation elicits a scant driving response bilaterally.  The epileptiform activity can be seen on one occasion during photic stimulation, but is not augmented by photic. Hyperventilation elicits a small amount of theta in the background.  Following this, drowsiness is characterized by a small amount of generalized background slowing.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Right central spike and slow wave activity with occasional brief bursts of spike and slow wave activity.
Subtle underlying focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy.  Because of the concomitant focal slowing, consideration for an underlying structural or functional abnormality rather than a benign localization-related epilepsy is appropriate, although this may still represent a somewhat unusual benign localization-related epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Right central spike and slow wave activity with occasional brief bursts of spike and slow wave activity. Subtle underlying focal slowing.

There is some variability towards the close of the record.  The periods with activity are a little bit longer lasting than those in the initial portions of the record and there is some higher amplitude theta there. Initial burst suppression pattern, which gradually improves as the recording continues.
Some shifting asymmetries with a breach rhythm.  Some portions of the record demonstrate a breach rhythm on the right with a bit more slower frequency activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a severe disturbance of cerebral function.  The improvement over the course of a brief EEG may be due to either improvement in this patient’s neurologic status, or the duration of time since his Phenobarbital infusion.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 2-year-old female who received a shunt in the right parietal region at six days of age for hydrocephalus.  Child now with staring spells for one to two minutes.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In the initial portions of the record, the child appears to be in light sleep.  The overall pattern at that time may include theta with some intermittent hypersynchronous rhythmic discharges.  There is a high amplitude vertex wave, which clearly spreads to involve C4 more significantly than the left central region.  With the use of an average reference, there seems to be underlying focal slowing with attenuation of faster frequency in the same region.  Thus, although the activity is maximum at the vertex and clearly spreads to C4, it is associated with underlying focal slowing and could not be considered a normal variant.  The child does reach stage II sleep with spindles, but this C4/CZ spike persists and as the child reaches stage II sleep, the focal slowing is more apparent.
HR:  140 BPM, occasionally irregular.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing in the right central and midline regions.
Sharp waves seen in drowsiness into stage II sleep, CZ/C4.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Despite the breach rhythm described above, this EEG suggests a partial mechanism for this patient’s epilepsy.  Correlation with imaging would be helpful in terms of localization.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Focal slowing in the right central and midline regions. Sharp waves seen in drowsiness into stage II sleep, CZ/C4.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 72-year-old woman with high-grade carotid stenosis; pre-op EEG.
MEDICATIONS: Heparin, Metformin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  There are intermittent bursts of focal slowing from the left hemisphere, maximum in the centrotemporal and posterior temporal regions.  Mixed with these bursts are occasional sharp waves identifiable at C3, T3, and T5.
Photic stimulation does not significantly activate the record, but there is a prominent burst, nearly 20 seconds long, of rhythmic theta from the left hemisphere, particularly from the centrotemporal regions.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Prominent focal slowing from the left hemisphere, particularly in the centrotemporal region.
Rhythmic theta with superimposed sharp waves and on one occasion with build-up of the theta frequency activity but without true evolution.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial mechanism for epilepsy, as well as an irritative cortex.  Additional evaluation of this patient for seizures is appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Prominent focal slowing from the left hemisphere, particularly in the centrotemporal region. Rhythmic theta with superimposed sharp waves and on one occasion with build-up of the theta frequency activity but without true evolution.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 45-year-old woman with multiple medical problems, increasing seizures, migraine headaches, Gilbert’s disease, and problems with crying, mumbling, and change in mental status.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax, Carbamazepine, and many others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record. No previous EEGs were available for comparison.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG demonstrates a 9.5 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm in a record rich in low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  When not stimulated, the patient drifts off to sleep with slow rolling eye movements, attenuation of the alpha rhythm, and an increase in background beta.  There had been crying earlier and the patient seems to have calmed down as she drifts off to sleep.  Brief stage I sleep is characterized by vertex waves.  At 15:37, the tech notes that the patient is not responding.
PHOTIC STIMULATION: The tech attempts to awaken the patient for additional testing.  The EEG shows a slightly awake or drowsy pattern, but the tech notes that the patient is not responding to verbal stimuli.  Photic stimulation continues.  The patient is awake at this time, and a driving response is identified.  In between the driving intervals, a well-defined alpha rhythm can be seen.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage I sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  It is not clear why the patient was not responding to the technologist’s commands.  She remained motionless and consideration for either excessive drowsiness or an emotional reaction may be appropriate. The background beta may be due to this patient’s medicines.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness through stage I sleep.

report:

1.	Focal right frontotemporal slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 41-year-old gentleman with a handful of seizures in 1998/1999 associated with severe emotional stress.
MEDICATIONS: Carbamazepine.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In wakefulness and drowsiness there is occasional temporal wicket.  There is also some 5 Hz rhythmic activity picked up in the left frontotemporal and frontocentral regions, left greater than right, but occasionally seen on the right. Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and accentuates the theta activity.  Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are some sharply contoured 5 Hz discharges identified in the temporal regions, left greater than right.  It is possible that these are normal variants including both wicket and rhythmic mid-temporal theta of drowsiness.  To determine whether or not this patient has underlying epileptiform activity, a study capturing deeper stages of sleep is required.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This EEG must be considered within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 71-year-old woman with adult onset epilepsy, seizure-free for many years with memory problems in the context of an otherwise bright, elderly woman.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and many others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.

1.	Excessive temporal theta and delta, which is at times sharply contoured.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to 1.Excessive temporal theta and delta, which is at times sharply contoured.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 91-year-old woman with a pacemaker, diabetes, hypertension, and a fall suffering a subdural hematoma.
MEDICATIONS: Antibiotics.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is intubated.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is somnolent throughout much of the record.  At this time, the EEG is markedly slow with a mixture of delta and smaller amounts of theta.  This poorly formed, periodic complex is seen in the record with a somewhat unusual field of spread picked up in the left frontal and right posterior quadrant.  Stimulation of the patient clearly produces an alerting response with an increase in theta.  In addition, there is also spontaneous arousals with an increase in theta.  Because of the movement artifact, it is difficult to determine if this periodic delta disappears.  It appears to attenuate to some extent with stimulation.
HR:  72 BPM, paced rhythm.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Marked background slowing particularly when the patient is not stimulated.
Poorly formed bilateral periodic complexes with an unusual field of spread without clinical correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a severe disturbance of cerebral function.  In the context of the patient’s age, these changes may be magnified.  No seizures were recorded and there were no prominent epileptiform features.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Marked background slowing particularly when the patient is not stimulated. Poorly formed bilateral periodic complexes with an unusual field of spread without clinical correlate.

High amplitude spike and slow wave complexes are most prominent in the right posterior region. There is also some high amplitude left anterior temporal spike and slow wave complexes. The epileptiform activity on the right is sometimes associated with some focal delta. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta. The spikes on the left seem to be accentuated in sleep. High amplitude eye movement artifact is noted. During photic stimulation, the patient seems to be falling asleep and falling off of the wheelchair. Myoclonic jerk was associated with epileptiform activity.
HR: N/A.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Epileptiform activity from the right posterior region
2. Independent left anterior spike and slow waves
3. Generalized background slowing and absence of some normal developmental milestones for an adult of this age
4. Occasional focal slowing in the right posterior quadrant
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports more than one possible pathway for seizures as well as a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Epileptiform activity from the right posterior region
2. Independent left anterior spike and slow waves
3. Generalized background slowing and absence of some normal developmental milestones for an adult of this age
4. Occasional focal slowing in the right posterior quadrant

report:

Left greater than right frontal delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This patient had a very limited stimulation, but when stimulated the EEG clearly showed an alerting response.  No definite epileptiform features were seen. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a more prolonged tracing capturing sleep cycle may be necessary given the breach rhythm.

report:
HISTORY: 63 yr old male with bilateral subdural hematoma, status post evacuation on the right with ischemia. Patient subsequently experienced cardiac an·est. Patient is comatose.
MEDICATION: Morphine, Phenobarbital, Phenytoin and Versed.

10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient has received Versed in close approximation to the EEG. No seizures are identified around the time of the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF  THE  RECORD: The  background  EEG demonstrates  a low  voltage but continuous  pattern.   The pattern  is variable.   There  are portions of the record with low voltage delta.  Intermittently, there is variability in the amount of theta. Breech rhythm can be identified on  the  right.    There  are  a  handful  of  subtle,  low  voltage  sharp  waves  seen  from  the  right. Stimulation  of the patient, including auditory stimulation,  seems to produce an increase in theta. Tactile stimulation most clearly produces an increase in theta.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This  EEG supports  a diffuse  disturbance  of cerebral  function affecting  both  gray  and  white matter.    In this individual  with  a craniotomy,  the  EEG  is low voltage than one might anticipate but the subdural hematoma may modify this. No seizures were recorded.  The variability and reactivity to stimuli are positive prognostic features.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.   Replacement  of normal background with a slow pattern
2.  Shifting asymmetries  with a bit more slow delta from the right compared  to left and rare low amplitude right frontocentral sharp waves

report:

MEDICATIONS: Antihypertensives, Ativan, and others.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 59-year-old male with a long history of diabetes, chronic pain who reports episodic sensation of hypoglycemia with dizziness and impaired responsive.  The patient reports that this occurred with serum glucose of 81.  Brief hypotensive spell this morning.
MEDICATIONS: Percocet, insulin, Digoxin, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is performed.  The patient seems quite drowsy, and rapidly drifts off to sleep in photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: When the patient is maximally awake, there is a 10 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  As he becomes drowsy, there is an increase in background theta with brief bursts of frontal delta in the transition to sleep.  Vertex waves are identified.  Sleep is not sustained, and he seems to drift off to sleep more rapidly. Photic stimulation elicits both an alerting response and brief driving.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within the limits of normal for a subject of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The tendency to drift off to sleep may be due to sleep deprivation or this patient’s medications.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within the limits of normal for a subject of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 42-year-old woman with severe, chronic static encephalopathy with frequent seizures. Multiple different seizure types are noted with myoclonus and staring.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote and Lamictal.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is slow with at best a theta frequency pattern.  There are frontally predominant generalized slow spike and wave discharges, as well as some rhythmic activity from the left frontal region.  The majority of the epileptiform discharges are present bilaterally, occasionally poly spike and wave, but occasionally seen independently from one hemisphere or the other.  There is variability in the record with some portions of the record showing more frontal delta and/or more spikes.  There are brief portions of the record with rhythmic alpha and theta frequency activity without clear clinical correlate.  There are also bursts of frontal delta, some of which have a poly spike or spike and wave complex, but some which occur without the poly spike activity.
Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
HR:  75 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slowing.
Slow spike and wave and poly spike and wave activity.
Bursts of frontal delta, sometimes left greater than right.
Rare multiple focal spikes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These features are compatible with a Lennox-Gastaut-type syndrome. There is a bit more focal pathology on the left compared to the right.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized slowing. Slow spike and wave and poly spike and wave activity. Bursts of frontal delta, sometimes left greater than right. Rare multiple focal spikes.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 61-year-old, right-handed male with a right frontal glioblastoma.
MEDICATIONS: Percocet, Dilantin, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed. Previous EEGs are not available for comparison.  The patient is somnolent and confused.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a continuous, low voltage mixed frequency pattern.  It is relatively homogeneous.  There is a subtle asymmetry with disruption of faster frequency activity from the right hemisphere compared to the left.  There are also a handful of left frontotemporal sharp waves.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in background beta.  Photic stimulation is associated with a brief dramatic alerting response.   There is also F3 alpha frequency activity artifact picked up.
HR:  110 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Severe background slowing.
Intrahemispheric asymmetry with greater slowing on the right compared to the left and disruption of faster frequency on the right.
Rare left anteriotemporal sharp waves.
An unusual area with rhythmic alpha frequency activity seen in photic stimulation and at other times, but without a clear correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe disturbance of cerebral function affecting both gray and white matter.  No seizures were recorded.  Correlation with imaging may be valuable.  Of note, this EEG was compared to previous records.  This EEG was obtained for an intraventricular hemorrhage, not a brain tumor.  Sharp waves were identified contralateral to the CNS lesion in previous studies.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Severe background slowing. Intrahemispheric asymmetry with greater slowing on the right compared to the left and disruption of faster frequency on the right. Rare left anteriotemporal sharp waves. An unusual area with rhythmic alpha frequency activity seen in photic stimulation and at other times, but without a clear correlate.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 56-year-old woman evaluated for clinical versus subclinical seizures following exploratory laparotomy, ileostomy, and ileostomy on 5/3/06.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Ativan, and morphine.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is stimulated and tested throughout the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a relatively low voltage pattern, which is subtly discontinuous with brief bursts of relatively homogeneous rhythmic theta and mixed delta followed by brief portions of attenuation or slower lower voltage delta.  The sections with attenuation are approximately two seconds in duration.  Stimulation of the patient produces some artifact, but also seems to give a small increase in background theta.  No clinical responses are noted to the stimulation.
HR:  114 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Replacement of normal background with a low voltage, subtly discontinuous pattern.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: To put this record into the appropriate clinical context, it is important to know the doses and degrees of Ativan and morphine this patient has received, as these medications could contribute to this record.  In all, this EEG supports a severe disturbance of cerebral dysfunction as can be seen with large doses of sedative hypnotic medications, severe toxic or metabolic encephalopathy, or other severe diffuse disturbances of cerebral function.  No epileptiform features were identified.  There was some small evidence of reactivity to stimuli.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Replacement of normal background with a low voltage, subtly discontinuous pattern.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 22-year-old, right-handed woman with hydrocephalus and right frontal shunt, status-post shunt revision two weeks ago with a single syncope versus seizure spell in 2003.
MEDICATIONS: Oral contraceptive, Detrol, Tylenol, Oxycodone, and Tylenol #3.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was omitted, but photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm identified with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Mixed theta is seen in drowsiness followed by vertex waves in stage I sleep.  Vertex waves and brief spindles are seen in stage II sleep.  In one section of the record with stage II sleep, slightly asymmetric vertex waves with a more remarkable field in the left central region were identified.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is initially asleep and does not clearly activate the record.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The slightly asymmetric vertex waves may be related to this patient’s previous craniotomy.  They were seen only in the transition to and from sleep.  If additional concerns remain regarding possible underlying epileptiform activity, an additional, more prolonged sleep recording using extra electrodes between Cz/C3 and Cz/C4 may be valuable.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is an 11-year-old, right-handed male with epilepsy since age 7 characterized by tonic-clonic seizures.  Last seizure two weeks ago.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age with a 10.5 Hz, 50 to 75 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, producing hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing, particularly from the occipital regions in the beginning.  Photic stimulation is characterized by vigorous driving with harmonic and supraharmonic driving.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in background theta.  At the close of the record, stage II sleep is recorded with vertex waves, spindles, K complexes, and POSTS.  There is some snore artifact, and there is a single right central sharp wave.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Only a single right centrotemporal sharp wave was noted in this record and, therefore, must be considered artifactual.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 71-year-old male with previous gunshot wound to the right occipitoparietal region at age 17 with a metal plate, Parkinson’s disease, epilepsy since 1976, and progressive gait disorder.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Nifedipine, and Diovan.  The patient is not on Sinemet.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is described as mildly confused. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a pattern with an 8 to 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with excess background theta and excess background beta.  There is little in the way of tremor artifact.  There is arrhythmic delta activity from the left temporal region with occasional left temporal sharp and slow wave complexes.  There is occasional arrhythmic delta from the right, but not with the same prominent burst of high amplitude, sharply contoured delta picked up from the left temporal region.  Features of drowsiness include rhythmic frontal delta.  Photic stimulation elicits a driving response including a supraharmonic driving response and an asymmetric driving response, more prominent on the right.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Intermittent arrhythmic delta activity from the left hemisphere.
Left temporal sharp waves.
Asymmetric driving.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In this individual with encephalomalacia on the right and a metal plate on the right, there is no epileptiform activity in that region.  However, there is epileptiform activity on the left, as well as focal slowing.  This may reflect the trajectory of the initial injury.  The metal plate may in some way attenuate the activity from the right.  These results are similar to previous studies.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Intermittent arrhythmic delta activity from the left hemisphere. Left temporal sharp waves. Asymmetric driving.

report:

report:

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a structural or functional abnormality on the left.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Continuous left frontotemporal delta with disruption of faster frequency activity. A moderate degree of background slowing from the right hemisphere with an interesting pattern, occasionally with the patient demonstrating snoring and very brief arousals from the right hemisphere, with an unusual arousal pattern emerging from sleep.
