Low voltage pattern.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  There is some shifting asymmetries identified in this record, but no strongly localizing findings.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to Generalized background slowing. Excess theta while awake. Low voltage pattern.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 60-year-old male who fell at home, developed a fever, weakness, and hypotension, possible CNS metastasis.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Neurontin, Digoxin, and Percocet.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is disorganized with prominent disruption of faster frequency activity.  There is arrhythmic delta activity and occasional triphasic waves are noted.  Shifting asymmetries are seen.  Stimulation of the patient does produce an increase in faster frequency activity.
HR:  120 BPM, irregular.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Marked background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No seizures or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The features described above are non-specific, but are compatible with a toxic or metabolic process and/or underlying bihemispheric process involving both gray and white matter.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Marked background slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 3-year-old, right-handed male with a staring spell one to two times per week.  An older brother has a history of seizures.
MEDICATIONS: none
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  The child is described as quite upset and agitated throughout the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the child is agitated, but there is an underlying 8 Hz posterior dominant rhythm at times reaching amplitudes close to 100 uV.  The father attempts to calm the child down with some success and there are some hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing as the child becomes drowsy.   Features of drowsiness include attenuation of the alpha rhythm with an increase in frontal fast activity and a handful of vertex waves. K complexes are seen in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
HR:  104 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and sleep for a child of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The normal developmental milestones for a child of this age have been met.  To evaluate a child for absence epilepsy, hyperventilation is an important test, but it does not appear that this child was able to participate in that test.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and sleep for a child of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 65-year-old woman with morbid obesity and multiple previous strokes, as well as carotid resection with intermittent weakness and falling.  The patient at one point suffered a black eye, but does not clearly remember hitting her head.  MRI demonstrated no evidence of new infarct.
MEDICATIONS: Heparin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is low voltage.  There is a glimpse of an 8.5 to 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm identified in the background.  Even at lower sensitivities, the EEG remains a relatively low voltage pattern. Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements and an increase in background theta.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is occasional temporal delta, left greater than right.  Photic stimulation does not clearly activate the record.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Modest generalized background slowing.
Subtle focal features from the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In a handful of normal individuals, it may be more difficult to identify an alpha rhythm, as was the case here.  Given the MRI, the focal features described above were less prominent than one might expect.  The generalized background slowing supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Modest generalized background slowing. Subtle focal features from the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 55-year-old male with HIV, asthma, diabetes, hypertension, with a five-year history of tonic-clonic seizures typically associated with Xanax withdrawal.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a low voltage, 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  There is the appearance of theta activity particularly in the frontocentral regions, prominent both in early drowsiness and in hyperventilation.  Vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS are identified in stage II sleep. In stage II sleep, there are a handful of vertex waves, which may phase reverse just slightly to the left or right of the midline.
Photic stimulation elicits a bilateral driving response.
HR:  120 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Very mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1.	What appears to be slightly asymmetric vertex waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There is a small amount of theta identified in this record early in drowsiness and in hyperventilation as can be seen in the context of HIV infection.  These slightly asymmetric vertex waves are of unclear clinical significance and may be correlated with imaging and history.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Very mildly abnormal EEG due to 1.What appears to be slightly asymmetric vertex waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 4-year-old male with an episode of nocturnal jerking and unresponsiveness for one to three minutes.  Born at 36-weeks gestation weighing 3 lbs. ½ oz.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm reaching amplitudes up to 100 uV.  Posterior slow waves of youth are identified.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with abundant vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.  Photic stimulation elicits a vigorous driving response.
HR:  108 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG for a child of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  This child demonstrated a vigorous driving response, which is a normal variant.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG for a child of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 56-year-old woman with hypertension and TIA in July 2006, admitted to Albert Einstein Medical Center.  No other details available.
MEDICATIONS: Aspirin, Norvasc, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  The patient is noted to be quite sleepy and to snore.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Features of drowsiness include attenuation of the alpha rhythm with abundant vertex waves and spindles seen in stage II sleep.  Snore arousals are identified in sleep.  There is also some buzzing auditory artifact, although this doesn’t produce a change in the EEG.  In the transition to and from stage II sleep, POSTS are quite prominent.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving at all flash frequencies.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. In this individual with prominent snore artifact, additional evaluation may be helpful to assess quality of sleep.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 3-year-old male with three seizures since July 14 characterized by tonic-clonic activity with eyes rolling back in the head, as well as two episodes of unresponsiveness and staring on July 21 lasting two to five seconds.  Last event 8/3/06
MEDICATIONS: None listed.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 8 Hz posterior dominant rhythm identified bilaterally, but higher amplitude on the left compared to the right.  Overall, there is an asymmetry between the two hemispheres with higher amplitude, faster frequency activity on the left in comparison to the right.  However, there is consistent single channel artifact from the left central electrodes all the way through the record.  MU rhythm was identified from the central regions bilaterally. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response that can be identified in the occipital scalp regions bilaterally, slightly more remarkable on the left compared to the right.
HR:  114 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Asymmetry between the two hemispheres with disruption of faster frequency on the right compared to the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Because of the technical features described above, this EEG should be repeated with attention to the electrodes on the left.  It is possible that this process involves the left rather than the right, but again, the test needs to be repeated with elimination of the electrodes and, if necessary, a more prolonged sleep study to get a good quality record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Asymmetry between the two hemispheres with disruption of faster frequency on the right compared to the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 57-year-old, right-handed woman with possible epilepsy, transferred from Dr. for refractory events.
MEDICATIONS: Topiramate, Keppra, Trileptal, and Zonegran.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was not possible, but  photic stimulation was completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is disorganized.  There is excess background theta and some shifting slowing.  In sleep, there are vertex waves identified.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is asleep and does not activate the record, although there are some spindles and other features of stage II sleep.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
Excess background slowing.
Shifting slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  An underlying and diffuse disturbance of cerebral function, including a bihemispheric process, could produce this pattern.  In addition, this patient’s medications may contribute to the pattern described above.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to Excess background slowing. Shifting slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 7-year-old male with a history of psychophysic visual disturbance and auditory hallucinations, bipolar disorder, ADHD, hypotonia, and developmental delay.
MEDICATIONS: Abilify.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz, 100 uV posterior dominant rhythm, with generous low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Posterior slow waves of youth were noted.  Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements and attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Stage II sleep is recorded during photic stimulation, and is characterized by vertex waves and spindles.  Hyperventilation produced an increase in the amplitude, and there were some bursts of occipitally predominant rhythmic occipital delta.  Photic stimulation elicits a brief driving response before the child falls asleep.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG for a child of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The generous beta could be due to anxiety or possibly this patient’s psychiatric medications.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG for a child of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 5-year-old male with one episode of loss of consciousness lasting two to five minutes with subsequent drowsiness.
MEDICATIONS: Vitamins.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 8 to 10 Hz alpha rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  The overall background is a high amplitude pattern, with the alpha rhythm reaching 100 uV. Occipital slowing is seen in the initial portions of the record, and becomes more organized as the patient calms down.  Drowsiness is characterized by hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing.  In stage II sleep, abundant vertex waves and spindles were seen. Hyperventilation produces abundant occipital slowing.  Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 48-year-old woman status-post PEA code for unknown period of time found down at home by a friend.  Patient was febrile at the time of admission with a temperature of 101.  Patient had seizures in the ER.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and Vancomycin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is described as intubated and unresponsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is markedly low voltage and suppressed.  There is low frequency of sweat artifact and generous muscle.  There is a suggestion of cerebral activity with occasional theta seen from the central regions and the left temporal region of about 5 to 6 Hz.  This is seen in only some portions of the record.  Stimulation of the patient may have produced some theta.
HR:  108 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Replacement of normal background with a very low voltage, suppressed pattern.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Because of the severity of suppression, consideration for a repeat tracing with a neuromuscular blocker might be appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Replacement of normal background with a very low voltage, suppressed pattern.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 46-year-old woman found down at home _________ with vomiting.  History significant for alcohol abuse, seizure disorder, and depression.
MEDICATIONS: Versed, Dilantin, antibiotics, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Portable digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  The patient is intubated and unresponsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is disorganized with superimposed excessively slow activity of theta and delta.  There is also a great deal of muscle movement artifact.  After the filter and sensitivity is adjusted, the excessive delta activity is also seen diffusely on the background.  The normal posterior dominant alpha rhythm is not identified.  After adjusting the sensitivity, the background appears to be somewhat asymmetric with attenuation on the right hemisphere.  Stimulation of the patient temporarily increases the slow waves, as well as increasing the amplitude on the background.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Disorganized background.
Background slowing with mild asymmetry with attenuation in the right hemisphere.
Absent alpha rhythm.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This abnormal EEG pattern is indicative of a cerebral dysfunction involving both gray and white matter, as well as the central nuclei in the midline.  The asymmetric EEG pattern may be suggestive of a structural abnormality.  Correlation with neuroimaging studies may be helpful.  However, the pattern is non-specific as to the etiology and can be seen in patients with encephalopathy secondary to metabolic, infectious, structural lesions, or postictal phase.  Clinical correlation is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Disorganized background. Background slowing with mild asymmetry with attenuation in the right hemisphere. Absent alpha rhythm.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 31-year-old male with who presents with new onset seizures with a fall and postictal confusion.  Length of seizures was not noted.
MEDICATIONS: Antihypertensives, Lasix, and Spironolactone.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is symmetric, continuous, but superimposed with excessive slow activity mostly in the theta and delta range.  There is a scant 9 Hz, 25 V posterior dominant alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing an increase in the posterior dominant alpha rhythm.  No abnormal responses were provoked.  Sleep is evidenced by decreased amplitude on the background with a mixed frequency of brain activity, as well as spindles and vertex waves.   Photic stimulation did not activate the record.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Background slowing with superimposed excessive theta and delta activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The above is a non-specific finding and can be seen in patients in the postictal phase due to medication or encephalopathy secondary to infectious, metabolic, or hypertensive etiologies.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  However, no focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If epilepsy is a clinical concern, a repeat EEG may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to 1.Background slowing with superimposed excessive theta and delta activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 64-year-old, right-handed woman with epilepsy since childhood with a seizure 09/10/06 with loss of consciousness followed by postictal drowsiness. Two previous EEGs did not identify epileptiform activity.
MEDICATIONS: Ibuprofen, Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm of 40 to 50 uV with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements.  Deeper stages of sleep are characterized by vertex waves and POSTS.  Hyperventilation does not significantly activate the record.    Photic stimulation does not alter the record.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  In this adult with lifelong refractory epilepsy and some relatively frequent tonic-clonic seizures, ambulatory outpatient EEG or inpatient EEG may be essential to characterize epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 41-year-old woman with adult onset epilepsy admitted with Dilantin toxicity, psychosis, and suicidal ideation
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Phenobarbital, Trileptal, and others. Positive tox screen for opiates.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is acceptably organized with a 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in theta.  There is generous background beta, and vertex waves are seen in sleep.
Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is relatively drowsy, but does produce a small amount of background slowing.
The single abnormality in this record is a pair of two left anteriotemporal sharp and slow wave complexes, maximum at T1 identified in wakefulness.  The first is a definitive sharp and slow wave and the second, which follows four seconds later, is more subtle.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Two left anteriotemporal sharp and slow wave complexes, maximum at T1 in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings support a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy.  In that there are two, they cannot be considered artifactual and they do occur in wakefulness.  The generous beta may be due to medication effect.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Two left anteriotemporal sharp and slow wave complexes, maximum at T1 in wakefulness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is an 81-year-old male with a history of dementia, hard of hearing, head trauma with subdural hematoma requiring bilateral ventriculostomy.  Patient had facial twitching 9/15/06.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is wearing a hard collar. This is an awake and drowsy record in a confused patient.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a pattern of theta of 4 to 5 Hz, with a small amount of frontocentral beta activity. There are occasional bursts of FIRDA, as well as some occipital delta.   There is no well-defined alpha rhythm, although there is likely some rocking artifact in the occipital electrodes.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
FIRDA.
Occasional occipital delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record, and no facial twitching was observed.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing. FIRDA. Occasional occipital delta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is an 85-year-old male with change in mental status and lethargy.  History of CHF, HTN, and mild hypothyroidism.
MEDICATIONS: Haldol, aspirin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there is an 8 to 9 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  The patient is lethargic throughout the record.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in background theta and delta.  There is spindle activity and some shifting delta.  Photic stimulation elicits a mild driving response.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
Mildly excessive theta while awake.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a mild disturbance of cerebral function.  Evaluation for the cause of this patient’s hypersomnolence may be appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to Mildly excessive theta while awake.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 59-year-old male with epilepsy since childhood and a stroke two years ago.  Patient is status-post head injury after falling from a third floor window in 1955 resulting in loss of consciousness for 15 days.  Last seizure in March 2006.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Stage II sleep is characterized by sleep spindles.  There are rare shifting asymmetries in stage II sleep.  Hyperventilation did not activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicits a mild driving response.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.  In light of this patient’s severe head trauma, the EEG is remarkably normal.  Clinical correlation is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 3-year-old male with afebrile seizures characterized by eyes rolling back in the head for five minutes, occurring once or twice per month.  Former 28-week gestation infant born weighing 3 lbs., 10 oz.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record. This is the third EEG for this individual.  The two previous EEGs indicated that he had febrile convulsions.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age with an 8.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  In sleep, vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are identified.
The major abnormality in this record, is discrete bursts of frontally predominant 3 Hz spike and wave activity seen in the transition to and from stage II sleep.  These are high amplitude discharges, typically occurring in discrete pairs, frontally predominant, symmetric, ranging from 3 to 3.5 Hz.  They can overlap with a spindle, which is a normal morphology of stage II sleep.  On one occasion, a pair of spike and wave complexes may be associated with an arousal.  At the close of the record, the child is stimulated from sleep, and occipitally predominant rhythmic slowing is followed by an awake pattern with LAMBDA when the child is more fully awake.
HR:  120 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	The appearance of frontally predominant, high amplitude spike and wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This activity was not seen in the two previous EEGs.  Correlation with this patient’s history may be helpful in that there were two previous EEGs demonstrating febrile convulsions with a child who may have developed afebrile convulsions and an EEG pattern that is most consistent with an inherited epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.The appearance of frontally predominant, high amplitude spike and wave activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 35-year-old male with possible syncope and sleep apnea.
MEDICATIONS: Unknown.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is a mainly asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is in sleep throughout much of the record.  Much of the record demonstrates stage II sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, spindles, and POSTS.  Attempts at stimulation such as in hyperventilation doesn’t produce much of an arousal pattern, but just prior to photic stimulation, the tech uses auditory stimulation and a well-defined, 11 Hz, 50 uV alpha rhythm is seen briefly until the patient falls off to sleep.  The tech attempts to keep the patient awake for photic stimulation, unsuccessfully.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is normal, but the patient does demonstrate hypersomnolence and the tech is having great difficulty keeping him awake during testing.  Additional evaluation with a sleep specialist may be necessary.  No epileptiform features were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 13-year-old female with daydreaming spells for two years.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This child had multiple absence seizures, some of which were clinically apparent even without cognitive testing.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background is well organized with an 11 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  LAMBDA activity is seen as is central MU.  In some cases the LAMBDA is somewhat asymmetric.
The major abnormality in this record is absence seizures characterized by bursts of rhythmic, high amplitude frontally predominant 3.5 to 5 Hz spike and wave activity with discharges lasting up to 10 seconds.  Clinical correlates of these three discharges include impaired recall of a code word and eye blinking, but during the fourth seizure, the patient actually seemed to gesture during her seizure.
Other abnormalities include occipitally predominant 4 Hz spike and wave activity, which seems to be bilateral and isolated, right or left temporal spike and slow wave complexes.  The major of the independent, right or left temporal spike and slow wave complexes were simple in nature, as may be seen in benign disorders, but in one case there was some additional focal slowing from the right.
Hyperventilation did appear to elicit one of these spells, although the absence seizures occurred spontaneously.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving.
HR:  96 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Four absence seizures lasting ten seconds in duration and associated with impairment of awareness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings were communicated by the tech on the day of the record in that this child is currently not treated with seizure medications.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Four absence seizures lasting ten seconds in duration and associated with impairment of awareness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 34-year-old woman with epilepsy - last seizure three months ago – tonic-clonic with postictal confusion.  History of recurrent or back-to-back seizures.  Last EEG 05/06.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record. This is the patient’s third EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10.5 Hz, 50 to 70 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by anterior spread of the alpha rhythm and an increase in background beta.  Hyperventilation does not activate the record.   Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Two previous EEGs were done in 2005 and 2006. The first was normal and the second showed subtle focal slowing from the right hemisphere.  In that none of the three EEGs have identified epileptiform activity, additional recording is appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 70-year-old woman, now 15-days status-post MVA with diffuse subarachnoid hemorrhage.  Patient was previously sedated but now has left gaze preference and right hemiparesis.  Also cervical hematoma.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing opens, the patient is intubated and wearing a hard collar.  The background demonstrates a continuous pattern, which is rich in theta and delta frequency activity.  There is an intrahemispheric asymmetry in that there is more theta on the right and a bit more slower delta on the left.
There is clear variability and reactivity in the record and some portions of the record demonstrate a pattern much richer in theta frequency activity with beta frequency activity, but the intrahemispheric asymmetry persists with a slower pattern on the left compared to the right.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in background delta.  This patient who is in isolation is stimulated only once and with this limited stimulation, there is limited evidence of reactivity.
HR:  114 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Intrahemispheric asymmetry with slower activity on the left.
Generalized background slowing with a pattern from the right, which is slow but is clearly reactive and variable and it sometimes has significant faster frequencies.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function, but consideration for a process impacting both gray and white matter in the left hemisphere is appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Intrahemispheric asymmetry with slower activity on the left. Generalized background slowing with a pattern from the right, which is slow but is clearly reactive and variable and it sometimes has significant faster frequencies.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 10-year-old female who had an episode of two to five seconds of generalized shaking during sleep occurring three to four times per night for the last two months.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is appropriately organized for a child of this age.  There is a 10 Hz, 50 to 70 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  Central MU rhythm is identified, but testing is not performed to confirm this.  Age appropriate quantities of background theta are noted.  Photic stimulation is associated with a vigorous driving response, as well as some LAMBDA activity, but there is no pathological activity.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in slowing of the background.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal awake EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: For this child who has strictly events in sleep, a study capturing sleep is essential.  This can be achieved either as a one-hour study or a sleep-deprived study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal awake EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 31-year-old woman with episodes of fading out two to three times per day with no loss of consciousness.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 12.5 Hz alpha rhythm with posterior slow waves of youth.  Alpha amplitude is 50 to 70 uV.  Stage II sleep shows abundant vertex waves, spindles, and POSTS.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in the amplitude of the background.   Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving with supraharmonic driving at essentially all flash frequencies.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal youthful EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The prominent driving response seen above is a normal finding.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal youthful EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 60-year-old woman with epilepsy, diabetes, asthma, daily angina who presented with a sudden frontal headache, shaking of the body, loss of consciousness, chest burning associated with a right basal ganglion hemorrhage.  History of incontinence and hallucinations.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is awake.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background is mildly slow with a posterior dominant rhythm averaging 7 Hz, 30 to 40 uV, and a small amount of diffuse background theta.  There is some shifting asymmetries noted in the record and in some portions of the record there seems to be a bit more, rhythmic theta frequency slowing from the right hemisphere in comparison to the left.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in background beta, as well as generalized theta.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Intermittent rhythmic slowing from the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The generalized background slowing is a non-specific finding and can be seen in a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function or postictal state.  The rhythmic background slowing from the right may be correlated with imaging.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to Generalized background slowing. Intermittent rhythmic slowing from the right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 49-year-old, right-handed woman with episodes of loss of consciousness, again beginning several months ago. Spells occur daily.  The patient has an aura, feeling the symptom coming on, and then blacks out and awakens.  The patient does not fall.  History of cervical disc disease requiring surgery and vocal cord injury.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background beta with some POSTS and some rhythmic temporal theta (wicket).  An additional normal variant noted in the left greater than right temporal region is 5 Hz rhythmic mid-temporal theta of drowsiness.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing a small amount of rhythmic background slowing.   Photic stimulation is performed just as the patient emerges from very brief stage I sleep with vertex waves.  A brief driving response is noted.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record, however, two normal variants were identified including one with rhythmic mid-temporal theta of drowsiness.  For this individual with frequent spells, a repeat study including either a prolonged sleep study or an outpatient ambulatory EEG may be helpful to further characterize her symptoms, particularly in light of a normal variant identified in drowsiness.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 19-year-old female with endocarditis and pneumonia who developed subarachnoid hemorrhage, seizures, and cardiac arrest.  Coded 9:50 PM on 12/4/06.  History of IV heroin abuse, TB, and embolism in the past.  Ativan given on 12/4/06.
MEDICATIONS: Clonidine, Percocet PRN, Ativan, Dilantin, dopamine.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG, and a portion of this record is also reviewed with ECS montage.  The patient is intubated, comatose, and unresponsive.  Body temp is 99, and systolic blood pressure is 62.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG activity is low voltage and markedly suppressed.  Portions of the record are reviewed with the ECS montage.  In this individual whose heart rate at times exceeds 150 BPM, there is clear EKG artifact, but there is also some 6 Hz activity, which is likely artifactual in nature but cannot be considered definitively artifact.  Some of this activity is also picked up in the non-cerebral electrodes.  No reactivity to external stimuli is noted.  There is no significant variability.
HR:  150 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Replacement of normal background with a suppressed pattern.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Because of the medical factors described above, this EEG cannot be used to confirm electrocerebral silence.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Replacement of normal background with a suppressed pattern.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 64-year-old woman with COPD exacerbation, past history of epilepsy, and stroke history with myoclonic jerks, tremors, or possible seizures associated with steroid use.
MEDICATIONS: More than fifteen including Ambien, Solumedrol, Levetiracetam, and antibiotics.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is markedly abnormal and includes a background that is intermittently reasonably well organized with a definable posterior dominant rhythm of approximately 7 Hz, 40 uV.  There are intermittent bursts of rhythmic frontal delta and/or triphasic waves.  There are also sharp waves identified in the record with variable maximum and a variable field of spread.  They may be in the left occipital or T5 left posterior temporal.  They have a generous field of spread in the bi-occipital regions and some of them have a different field in the left posterior temporal region, but involving the centroparietal areas as well.  The sharp waves can be seen in association with the bursts of FIRDA or triphasic waves, or independently.  Photic stimulation does seem to elicit a driving response at faster flash frequencies.
Features of drowsiness include an increase in the FIRDA.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Intermittent bursts of FIRDA.
Bursts of triphasic waves.
Epileptiform activity primary from the left hemisphere with an unusual spread.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The FIRDA and the triphasic waves suggest that there may well be an underlying metabolic encephalopathy.  This may accentuate the epileptiform activity described above.  No seizures were recorded, however, this is a very abnormal background.  Additional clinical evaluation may be important.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Intermittent bursts of FIRDA. Bursts of triphasic waves. Epileptiform activity primary from the left hemisphere with an unusual spread.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 46-year-old male with a history of seizures, now with breakthrough seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an alpha rhythm of 9 Hz, 30 uV.  There is a generous amount of artifact in the background.   Hyperventilation does not produce a significant change.  In drowsiness, there is background slowing.  Photic stimulation does not elicit a significant driving response.
HR:  84BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If further characterization of this patient’s seizures is necessary, a repeat EEG capturing deeper stages of sleep would be beneficial.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 52-year-old male with right-sided weakness, slurred speech in October, found to have right carotid artery disease.  History of stroke, hypertension, cervical laminectomy, CABG, and mitral valve replacement.
MEDICATIONS: Nicotine patch, Ambien, Zofran, Heparin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG includes a symmetric, reactive alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  In the transition to drowsiness, there is an increase in background theta and there is a subtle asymmetry with a bit more theta from the left hemisphere than the right.  This is a bit more prominent in the temporal regions than the central regions.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:  55-60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
1.	Subtle focal slowing identified in the transition to drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to 1.Subtle focal slowing identified in the transition to drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 52-year-old woman with diabetes, hypertension, heart failure, left MCA/CVA 06/06 admitted with a seizure due to antiepileptic drug non-compliance.
MEDICATIONS: Advair, Hydralazine, Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record in a patient who is uncomfortable.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Much of the record includes a drowsy pattern with background theta.  There is a transition to and from stage II sleep with vertex waves and spindles.  There is an intrahemispheric asymmetric noted intermittently with intermittent rhythmic delta from the left hemisphere particularly the temporal region. Intermittent rhythmic slowing can be identified in wakefulness, which also includes at times a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.   Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is falling off to sleep, but a trace driving response is seen.
HR:  104 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	Intermittent rhythmic slowing from the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definite epileptiform features were identified in this record.  An additional recording in the lab when the patient is a bit more comfortable may be helpful to further characterize epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.Intermittent rhythmic slowing from the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 46-year-old woman with a history of epilepsy since 1996 characterized by loss of consciousness and postictal seizures, now with ongoing staring spells – last staring spell 12/27/06.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a well-organized background with an 11 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background beta and attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Hyperventilation does not activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicits a photomyogenic and vigorous driving response, but not a photoparoxysmal response.
HR:  72 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  If further characterization of this patient’s frequent, staring spells is important, either a more prolonged study or an ambulatory study capturing one of her spells may be valuable.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is an 81-year-old male transferred from an outside hospital after pneumococcal pneumonia with meningitis, left ventriculitis, and stroke, as well as poor responsiveness.
MEDICATIONS: Insulin, Amiodarone, and Vancomycin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is intubated and poorly responsive, however, there is a great deal of muscle and other movement artifact.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is markedly abnormal and includes a mixture of theta and delta.  In addition, there are some frontally predominant triphasic waves and there are also occasional, independent periodic sharp complexes identified from either frontal region.  Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in theta frequency activity.
HR:  66 to 80 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Independent frontal periodic sharps.
Triphasic waves.
Replacement of normal background with generalized background slowing and a mixed frequency pattern with theta and delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.  There are irritative features including the occasional frontal periodic sharp complexes and metabolic features including the triphasic waves.  Correlation with clinical picture and imaging is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Independent frontal periodic sharps. Triphasic waves. Replacement of normal background with generalized background slowing and a mixed frequency pattern with theta and delta.

report:
CLINICAL  HISTORY: This is a 69-year-old  Latin teacher with a chronic subdural hematoma, dementia, depression, and weight loss.
MEDICATIONS: Aricept, Nexium, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10Hz,  40 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements.
HR:  78 BPM. IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL  CORRELATION:  Despite the  memory impairment and the  subdural hematoma, there are no abnormalities identified in this EEG.  No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL  HISTORY: This is a 58-year-old woman with CVA two months ago with left-sided weakness and previous right MCA/CVA, now with possible complex partial seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record with photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE  RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an 11 Hz, 50 to 70 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by slowing of the background and an increase in the prominent beta.  Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving identifiable bilaterally, but better represented on the left compared to the right.
HR:  96BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL  CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record. The somewhat asymmetric driving response is of unclear clinical significance, but may be relevant to this patient's previous stroke.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL  HISTORY:  This   is   a   55-year-old   male   with   seizure   and  loss   of
consciousness  7/06 and seven-day  hospitalization.   No clear cause for the seizure.   No other details known.
MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital  video  EEG is  performed in  the lab  using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE  RECORD: In wakefulness, the background is well organized with a symmetric, reactive posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. As the patient becomes drowsy, there is a small an1ount of background theta.   Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements. Hyperventilation produces a small amount of background slowing.    Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is relatively drowsy.  No significant driving response is seen. Lateral rectus artifact is noted.
HR: 78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 43-year-old male with new onset seizures in June 2006.  Last seizure was two weeks ago associated with loss of consciousness and tonic-clonic activity followed by postictal confusion lasting a few minutes.  Patient denies any current injury or head trauma.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote and Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF  THE  RECORD: In wakefulness, there  is  a  10  Hz,  50  uV poste1ior dominant rhythm.  The patient has shaking of his head from side to side.   This is noted in the waking background.   Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record.   The patient has increased shaking of his head from side to side during hyperventilation, but remains responsive with the technologist.   The shaking produces muscle artifact.   The patient appears to be very nervous.  No pathological abnormalities were seen in hyperventilation.   Hyperventilation was followed by brief drowsiness, but deeper stages of sleep were not achieved.
During photic stimulation, the patient had tremulousness of his hands, shaking of his head back and forth, and unusual vocalizations. These behaviors were associated with muscle a1iifact in the EEG, but no epileptiform activity.    The patient also had shaking from side to side and up and down with asynchronous movements.  The behaviors lasted for four minutes.  After the patient stopped moving around, LAMBDA waves were seen followed by an alpha rhythm.   As this prolonged behavior resolved, the patient has shaking of his right hand and "feels like hell."
HR:  70 BPM increasing to 120 BPM with the spells. IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This patient's behaviors were not associated with epileptiform activity. In addition, they were prolonged, waxing and waning.   The patient appeared to be anxious with these behaviors. Consideration for a non-epileptic process is appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 48-year-old male found hypothermic.   Patient fell on ills face, had  tremulousness, a blood  glucose  of  48, and  was intoxicated  with  crack cocaine.  Hypoglycemia, hypothermia  and cocaine intoxication. The date of this patient's
collapse and neurologic symptoms is not known, but the EEG was recorded on the 7th.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Vancomycin, others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode  placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record with photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION
OF  THE  RECORD: In  wakefulness,  the background  EEG  is  low
voltage.    The  patient  is  primarily drowsy,  but  with stimulation  a posterior  dominant rhythm is identified  of 9 Hz.   There is a small amount of background beta and a small amount  of  background   mixed  theta  and  delta  noted  even  in  the  maximal   waking background.   Features of stage I sleep include vertex waves.   Spindles are identified in stage II sleep.
Photic  stimulation  is  performed  while  the  patient  is falling  asleep,  but  does  elicit  a driving response.
HR: 110 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Mild excess beta.
2.  Mild excess theta and delta in apparent wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: For  an individual  with  these severe  CNS insults, this EEG  carries  a positive  prognosis.    The  background  slowing  described above is non­ specific and could be related to hypoglycemia, hypothermia, or other acute metabolic encephalopathies.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to 1. Mild excess beta. 2.  Mild excess theta and delta in apparent wakefulness.

report:

MEDICATIONS: Ativan.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm. There is intermittent, shifting arrhythmic delta activity with at times a bit more arrhythmic delta activity from the right and attenuation of faster frequency activity from the right frontal regions. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
HR: 72BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Occasional shifting slowing.
2. Occasional focal slowing from the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record. This EEG supports a structural or functional abnormality on the right, as well as a bihemispheric process.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Occasional shifting slowing. 2. Occasional focal slowing from the right.

report:
CLINICAL   HISTORY:  This  is  an  81-year-old  male  with  diabetes,  hypertension, incontinence,  and Alzheimer's  disease, found unresponsive with  confusion for two to three hours.
MEDICATIONS:  Lisinopril, Synthroid, Detrol, others.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 73-year-old woman with renal failure on dialysis. Evaluate for change in mental status.   Significant cortical atrophy and old cerebral infarcts.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is intubated and poorly responsive.

HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.  Marked background slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	82-year-old male found unresponsive with right ACA/ MCA watershed infarct and 2nd left MCA infarct. Patient found not moving his right side.
INTRODUCTION: 	Digital video 	EEG is performed using standard
10/20 system electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is intermittently  agitated.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: 	The background EEG demonstrates a mixed frequency pattern with rhythmic background slowing but at times there is a slow posterior dominant rhythm. Bursts of rhythmic, bilateral delta as well as arrhythmic delta activity are noted. Intermittently, asymmetries are identified with the more rhythmic slowing from the left frontal region.
HR: 	75 BPM - Irregular
IMPRESSION: 	Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing and poor organization.
2. Intermittent rhythmic slowing from the left frontal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: 	No epileptiform features were identified. This EEG supports a bi-hemispheric process.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Generalized background slowing and poor organization. 2. Intermittent rhythmic slowing from the left frontal region.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	A 25-year-old right-handed male who has a history of electrocution at the age of 6, followed by epilepsy at age 17, 2-3 seizures per month characterized as tonic clonic with loss of consciousness, tongue biting, postictal headache and drowsiness.
MEDICATIONS: 	Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using 10-20 electrode system placement and 1-lead of EKG.  Photic stimulation and hyperventilation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: 	In wakefulness, there is 9.5-Hz alpha rhythm which is symmetrical and reactive. 	Drowsiness is characterized by slowness of the alpha rhythm with vertex waves and spindles in
stage 2 sleep. 	Lateral rectus eye movement artifact is picked up on the left in wakefulness and 	interestingly in sleep. 	In transition to sleep, there is a 1.5-second burst of frontally dominant 3-Hz spike
and wave activity. 	There is another burst of fast spike and wave
activity as he drifts off to sleep. 	Hyperventilation did not activate the record. 	Photic stimulation elicited a driving response, although he was falling asleep.
HR: 	60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: 	This is a normal EEG due to frontally dominant spike wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: 	This EEG is more supportive of inherited mechanism of epilepsy, although a frontal lobe focus can also produce a similar pattern. 	Comparison with previous EEGs can be helpful. Consider fasting and sleep-deprived record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This is a normal EEG due to frontally dominant spike wave activity.

report:
CLINICAL  HISTORY:	60-year-old with stroke  2003  and several TIAs, 	now with episodic light-headedness and dizziness  with an aura  of numbness on the right  side of her body, evaluation  for syncope.
MEDICATIONS: 	None.
INTRODUCTION: 	Digital  video EEG  is performed in lab  using standard 10/20  system of electrode  placement with  1  channel EKG. Photic stimulation 	performed  by hyperventilation is deferred.
DESCRIPTION   OF  THE  RECORD:	The patient is drowsy  throughout much  of the record, but brief  portions of wakefulness,		included a  9    Hz  symmetric  reactive posterior dominant rhythm.	In  the transition to and from drowsiness,	there  is rare right or left temporal slowing.	Photic stimulation of scant driving.
HR:    90  BPM.
IMPRESSION: 	EEG within  normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL   CORRELATION:	No epileptiform features  are identified in this record. 	There  were occasional PVCs  observed. Additional evaluation may  be warranted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within  normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	This is a right handed female, 49 years old with new onset epilepsy with first episode while driving 8 months ago with loss of consciousness and confusion.
MEDICATIONS: 	None.
INTRODUCTION: 	Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photo stimulation were performed. 	This was an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION  OF THE RECORD: 	In wakefulness, background EEG is well organized with 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. 	Vertex waves and spindles are identified in stage 2 sleep.
The major abnormality 	identified in this record was seen in hyperventilation. 	Hyperventilation produced 3 bursts lasting just under 3 seconds characterized by frontally predominant symmetric, high amplitude, spike and wave activity. 	A similar suspicious burst was identified with just a pair of spike and wave complexes identified
when the patient is awakened at the end of the record for photo
stimulation. 	Photo stimulation was performed while the patient was drifting in and out of stage 2 sleep, however, they close with hyperventilation 	as the patient goes back to sleep, another spike and wave complex is noted.
HR: 	66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: 	Abnormal EEG due to frontally predominant 3-5 hertz spike and wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In the presence of a normal background, these findings are most commonly seen in inherited epilepsy syndromes.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to frontally predominant 3-5 hertz spike and wave activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	The patient is a 40-year-old male who was admitted on May 30, 2007, status post motorcycle accident with no helmet with multiple injuries resulting in both "down-time" of 20 to 25 minutes as well as head trauma. The patient "coded" on May 29, 2007, at 3 AM.
MEDICATIONS: 	Depakote, Dilantin, Versed, Propofol.
INTRODUCTION: 	Digital video EEG is performed at bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electro-placement  with 1 channel of EKG. The EEG demonstrates jerking of the patient including mouth and shoulders.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: 	Background EEG is markedly abnormal. There is cerebral activity identified bilaterally. There is sharply contoured paroxysmal approximately 3 Hz activity in the occipital regions, some of which seems to have an underlying sharper spike or fast component with it. This does not entirely correlate with the twitching, and the twitching is typically a very rapid myoclonic jerk with a different frequency. The occipitally predominant pattern is not clearly associated with a sustained motor phenomenon. In some sections of the record, the activity is clear. The epileptiform activity in the occipital regions is clearly maximum on the right. Some of the myoclonic jerking almost produces a clear EEG correlate that can be seen
by the camera, although it is seen by the tech, and at other
times the jerking can be witnessed, but overall the camera seems to underestimate the activity. Towards the close of the record, the myoclonic jerking seems to have abated, but the occipitally predominant slowing with this underlying fast discharge
persists.
HR: 140 bpm
IMPRESSION: 	Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Occipitally predominant focus of epileptiform activity, right greater than left without clear clinical correlate.
3. Clinical myoclonus without clear EEG signature.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Generalized background slowing

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:	A 79-year-old male with dementia, right AKA, epilepsy and a CT scan with multiple, acute hemorrhages, history of lupus.
MEDICATIONS:	Dilantin, labetalol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at bedside in the ICU using a standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not possible.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:	Background EEG includes a mixed frequency background rich in beta and delta activity. There is an interhemispheric asymmetry with greater, faster frequency activity on the right compared to the left. The left includes arrhythmic delta activity. In addition, some sections of the record include arrhythmic, somewhat pruritic delta maximum from the left hemisphere, particularly the temporal region. There is variability in the record with some sections richer and faster frequency than others. In addition, not all sections of the record show the periodic sharp activity. Stimulation
of the patient produces faster frequency activity from both hemispheres, right greater than left.
HR: 120 bpm
IMPRESSION: 	Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Marked background slowing.
2. Interhemispheric asymmetry.
3. Intermittent bursts of arrhythmic delta activity identified from the left hemisphere with periodic complexes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:	Although no seizures were recorded, this EEG raises concerns for an epileptogenic process on the left. Additional EEG recording may be an appropriate consideration.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Markedly abnormal EEG due to 1. Marked background slowing. 2. Interhemispheric asymmetry. 3. Intermittent bursts of arrhythmic delta activity identified from the left hemisphere with periodic complexes.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 21-year-old with epilepsy since age 12 and multiple different types of events, some of which resembled syncopal spells. Seizure free aside from 4 seizures in sleep in March 2007.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, folate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, background EEG included the 9.5 posterior dominant rhythm a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity. There is a small amount of background theta. In relaxed wakefulness, there are a handful of subtle sharp waves from the left or right temporal region. Most of them are small and discreet, but some have a more of a broader morphology, although they are never high in amplitude. They lack the simplicity of benign epileptiform transience of sleep. The patient has stimulated for hyperventilation and these morphologies disappear. Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing an increase in background theta. There is a suggestion that it may also accentuate an arrhythmic delta from the left with independent right and left temporal sharp and slow wave, or spike and slow wave complexes. The epileptiform activity identified in hyperventilation was denoted on the record. Towards the close of the record, high amplitude right inter temple spike and slow wave complexes with generous field of spread were observed. As the patient becomes drowsy, the right temporal sharp waves are again well defined and the left temporal features are not as commonly identified. Other features of sleep include vertex waves and posts. Photic stimulation elicits harmonic with supra harmonic striving.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Right anterior temple spike and slow wave complexes accentuated by hyperventilation and seen in the transition from wakefulness into drowsiness.
2. Occasional more poorly defined left temporal sharp waves.
Clinical correlation: For this young adult with a strong family history of epilepsy, this study today is most supportive of a localization related mechanism with a right inter temple sharp wave with a generous field of spread. There is a remarkably bigger striving response, but not a clearly pathological one.
Additional review of the epilepsy in the family would be important to know if this individual's epilepsy is similar or just similar to other members in the kindred. In contrast to previous studies, the vast majority of epileptiform features today were on the right rather than the left.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Right anterior temple spike and slow wave complexes accentuated by hyperventilation and seen in the transition from wakefulness into drowsiness

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	60-year-old woman with a history of head trauma, lethargy, and a subdural hematoma. The patient was admitted November 15, 2007. Date of neurosurgery is unknown. History of COPD, BKA, and multiple other medical problems.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Coumadin, Dilantin, Antibiotics.
INTRODUCTION: 	Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using the standard
10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient has a temperature of 104.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Background EEG is markedly abnormal. The activity includes a very low voltage pattern with featureless delta. Breech rhythm is identified from the left with a burst of delta in that region as well as accentuation of fast activity in the context of the breech rhythm. Using different montages, it is clear that there is an area of focal positivity, not negativity at F3. Stimulation of the patient does not activate the record.
HR: 	132 bpm
IMPRESSION:   Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
1. 	Replacement  of normal background  with relatively low voltage, featureless pattern.
2. 	A focus of electro positivity in the left frontal region.
3. 		Breech rhythm, but with some accentuation of frontal fast activity identified left greater than right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe underlying encephalopathy. No epileptiform features were seen and no focal features were seen in the region of the patient's craniotomy. In the absence of sedative hypnotic medications, this EEG demonstrates  a worrisome pattern in terms of the severity of encephalopathy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:   Markedly abnormal EEG due to 1. Replacement  of normal background  with relatively low voltage, featureless pattern. 2. A focus of electro positivity in the left frontal region. 3. Breech rhythm, but with some accentuation of frontal fast activity identified left greater than right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:   A 71-year-old  found unresponsive  on an unknown date and coded at
4:00 a.m. on 12/26/2007 for four minutes.  History of arthritis and alcohol abuse.
MEDICATIONS:   Heparin, Nexium, Haldol, Thiamine, Hydrocortisone, Lorazepam, Clonidine, Insulin, Unasyn
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement  with 1 channel of EKG 6 hours after the cardiac arrest.  The patient is intubated.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  It is suppressed with brief apex of high amplitude activity.  There is no audio on the video.  The patient is tachypneic, and has intermittent bursts of paroxysmal high amplitude activity which may occur once per minute, or as often as 3 times in a minute.   Over time, reviewing the entire record, it is clear that the patient has a small hiccup which sometimes produces jerking of his head with the events.  This is best observed when reviewing the EEG and a fixed rate of 60 seconds per page.  There is also a triangular-shaped  wave form in the right occipital region with some
spread to the left that may occur as often as 4 times in a 20 second period or 10 times in a second.
HR: 	120 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG, performed acutely after cardiac arrest due to:
1.	Suppressed background.
2. 	Intermittent bursts of cerebral activity.
3. 	A triangle-shaped wave form in the occipital region.
CLINICAL CORR ELATION:
These findings with a burst suppression pattern, sense of
reactivity of variability and a triangular-shaped  wave-form in the background  are concerning in this context.  Additional clinical evaluation is advised in that this is a hyperacute pattern.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG, performed acutely after cardiac arrest due to 1.Suppressed background. 2. Intermittent bursts of cerebral activity. 3. A triangle-shaped wave form in the occipital region.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  61 year-old male status post left occipital stroke, status post cardiac arrest 12/22 with 30 minute arrest and complicated hospital stay.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Zosyn, Hydralazine, Heparin, Zosyn, Insulin, Solu Medrol, Nexium, Metoprolol, Rifaximin
INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG is performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient is intubated and responds to tactile stimuli by moving about.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  The most prominent features are a posteriorly predominant periodic complex which appears maximum in the right rather than the left.  The periodic sharp activity in this record has variable fields and variable maximum, including 02, T6 and even F8 phase reversal. Other maxima for these periodic complexes include the left frontal region.  Stimulation
of the patient produces an arousal, as described above.  There are independent,
periodic sharp waves observed from either hemisphere, some of which are asynchronous and some of which are seen exclusively unilateral on the left or the right, although the right occipital seems to be the most prominent discharge in this record. The background includes smaller amounts of irregular theta and delta as well as intermittently discontinuous pattern.  Periods of suppression which are one second in duration typically occur after an occipital high amplitude periodic sharp wave.  Agitation including movement of the patient's head is not associated with ictal change.  On one occasion there is a brief build up of the right occipital sharp waves.
HR: 	72  bpm
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
1. 	Periodic complexes from multiple locations in both hemispheres.
2. 	A brief buildup of right occipital sharp waves.
3. 	Markedly abnormal background.
4. 	Intermittently  discontinuous pattern.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a very irritative process.   In addition, the discontinuity  and the markedly abnormal background  are worrisome features following cardiac arrest.  Additional evaluation for some clinical seizures as well as evaluation of the severity of this patient's anoxic encephalopathy is warranted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to 1. Periodic complexes from multiple locations in both hemispheres. 2. A brief buildup of right occipital sharp waves. 3. Markedly abnormal background. 4. Intermittently  discontinuous pattern.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:   68-year-old,  right handed woman with a history of epilepsy, seizure-free for the last 5 years with low dose Dilantin, admitted with nystagmus and found to have a PICA stroke.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin
INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. As the patient becomes drowsy there is an increase in theta. In addition, shifting arrhythmic delta activity, some of which is sharply contoured on the left with a subtle underlying sharp wave is observed. As the patient becomes drowsier, shifting arrhythmic delta can be seen from either temporal region. Some of this focal slowing on the right is posterior temporal. Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR: 	60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:   Abnormal EEG due to:
1. 	Shifting arrhythmic delta from the right or left hemisphere.
2. 	Some sharply contoured slowing from the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   The focal slowing described above is nonspecific in an adult of this age. Correlation with imaging and a history of cerebrovascular disease may be helpful as this kind of slowing is commonly seen in that age group. There is some sharply contoured slowly and some subtle sharp waves on the left in this individual with a past history of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:   Abnormal EEG due to 1. Shifting arrhythmic delta from the right or left hemisphere. 2. Some sharply contoured slowing from the left.
