report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 62-year-old male with a left MCA stroke, dizziness, headache,
hypersomnolence after receiving morphine, history of gunshot wound in 1980 and left
leg weakness. No prior history of seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Aggrenox, Atenolol, Isosorbide, Lovastatin, Lisinopril, Prilosec
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at bedside using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Background EEG demonstrates an
intrahemispheric asymmetry. There is focal slowing from the left in comparison to the
right. There is disruption of faster frequency activity as well as some sharply contoured
activity in the left temporal region. The patient intermittently arouses, but does not
maintain that level of arousal. As he drifts off to sleep, bursts of sharply contoured focal
slowing and subtle actual sharp waves are observed in the left hemisphere with atypical
phase reversal T1, but occasionally T3 or T5. Vertex waves and spindles were
observed in stage 2 sleep. In the sleep section, the epileptiform activity transitions to a
left posterior temporal focus. In addition, there are also POSTS observed bilaterally.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1 .
Focal slowing from the left with sharply contoured delta and sharp waves mid to
anterior temporal in wakefulness transitioning to posterior temporal in sleep.
2.
Hypersomnolence.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a structural abnormality on the left.
The epileptiform features suggest a predisposition to seizures. The hypersomnolence
may be due to the use of sedative hypnotic medication. If clinically indicated, additional
observation for an underlying seizure disorder is appropriate.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1 . Focal slowing from the left with sharply contoured delta and sharp waves mid to
anterior temporal in wakefulness transitioning to posterior temporal in sleep. 2. Hypersomnolence.

report:

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.

movements, arrhythmic delta and then intermittently even, vertex waves and spindle activity followed by arousal.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:

slowing described above is non-specific and may be due to CNS, HIV disease, postictal

IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Generalized background slowing. 2. A dynamic pattern of intermittent arousal was followed by drifting off into a slower pattern compatible with drowsiness or a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 67-year old woman with metastatic brain lesions, status post left parietal lobectomy, history of seizures in November with shaking lasting 5-10 minutes.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Keppra, steroids, antihypertensive.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement of 1 channel EKG. Photic stimulation is completed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Background EEG demonstrates a somewhat slow background bilaterally but at times alpha rhythm on the left reaches 10.5 Hz. Notable features include an intra-hemispheric asymmetry with disruption of fast and frequency activity on the right compared to the left, high amplitude delta, particularly in the right posterior quadrant and a subtle sharp wave observed at C4. As the patient becomes drowsy, focal delta is localized primarily to the right posterior quadrant. Photic stimulation: A subtle driving response is observed as is a breech rhythm with accentuation of faster frequency in the right central parietal region.
HR: 64 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Focal slowing in the right hemisphere with underlying delta, maximum in the right posterior quadrant.
2. Right central sharp waves.
3. Mild background slowing bilaterally.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a structural abnormality on the right as well as a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy. The mild bilateral background slowing may be correlated clinically.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Focal slowing in the right hemisphere with underlying delta, maximum in the right posterior quadrant. 2. Right central sharp waves. 3. Mild background slowing bilaterally.

system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is intubated and

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There are brief portions in the record where the
patient is calm, but awake. The background EEG at this time includes some alpha
frequency activity with a hint of a 1 0 Hertz alpha rhythm on the left. It is also seen on
occasion on the right. There is some superimposed focal slowing observed in the right
hemisphere in relaxed wakefulness. Features of drowsiness include attenuation of
alpha and theta frequency activity as well as some delta. There is also some occasional
head rocking, but a suggestion of some right frontal delta.
HR: 120 bpm.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Intermittent focal slowing from the right.
2. Intermittent generalized background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The single sharp wave from the left is an unanticipated
finding. Given the context of this, the patient's high fever, and potential for sweat artifact,
if seizures are an· important consideration, reevaluation of the left temporal sharp wave
is recommended. Focal slowing on the right with disruption of fast or frequency activities
is congruent with a history of a MCA cortical infarct.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Intermittent focal slowing from the right. 2. Intermittent generalized background slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 20 year-old with paroxysmal vomiting.
MEDICATIONS: Zofran, Fentanyl patch, Cymbalta, others.
INTRODUCTION: Continuous video EEG monitoring is performed at bedside using standard
10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is evaluated for
intermittent paroxysmal vomiting. Paroxysmal vomiting or nausea occurred on 2 occasions,
including 20:37 and 21 :34.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, the background EEG demonstrates
a small amount of background theta. The patient is otherwise comfortable. Features of
drowsiness include rhythmic background slowing. The patient is observed to take off his
electrodes towards the close of the record. The overnight sleep recording demonstrates
relatively disrupted sleep, but evidence of slow-wave sleep is observed.
Vomiting #1: Time 20:37. The EEG at this time demonstrates an awake pattern. The EKG lead
is not interpretable. The video camera actually comes back and the video is visible. Although
there is muscle and movement artifact, there is no evidence of epileptiform activity at this time.
Vomiting #2: Time 21 :34. The patient is on camera. The light is darkened, but the patient can be
seen to be lying on his back and moving about. Again, the EKG lead is not functional, but no
epileptiform activity is observed at this time.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG monitoring due to:
1. background theta.
CLINICAL The background theta in wakefulness can be seen in the context
of narcotic administration. No epileptiform features were observed.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG monitoring due to 1. background theta.

report:

hyperventilation, the EEG is somewhat better organized, and a little bit more rhythmic as the patient starts to become drowsy, but the posterior-dominant rhythm remains slow. report:
CLINICAL CORRELATION: 65-year-old right-handed female with an aneurysm repair in
1987, TIA in 2000 with global confusion. History of epilepsy which began after the
aneurysm surgery but after the 2000 TIA. Seizure-free since
2000.
MEDICATIONS: Gabapentin, Enalapril, Tegretol, Lovastatin, HCTZ,
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in lab using standard 10-20 system
of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is observed to have a right
craniotomy defect. Photic stimulation is performed. This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the alpha rhythm is present
bilaterally but a bit disrupted on the right. It reaches 8.3 Hz maximum. There is a clear
intra-hemispheric asymmetry as well as a craniotomy defect and a breach rhythm.
Faster frequency activity in wakefulness is initially disrupted on the right. In addition,
there is arrhythmic delta activity in the right hemisphere with an underlying right mid to
posterior temporal region, phase reversal at T4 but at times nearly isoelectric at T4/T6. As the patient transitions in and out sleep, this sharp wave on 1 occasion appears
maximum at T 4. In addition, as the patient transitions into sleep, the breach rhythm
becomes more prominent. As beta frequency activity increases in drowsiness, the beta
is accentuated in the right frontal region. Photic stimulation does elicit a driving
response although the patient is drifting off to sleep in photic. The photic driving
response is more vigorous on the left in comparison than the right. It is also confounded
by the fact that intermittently she started to fall off to sleep and POSTS are observed.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Intra-hemispheric asymmetry with focal slowing on the right, arrhythmic delta
activity on the right.
2. Right mid to posterior temporal sharp wave.
3. Single right parietal sharp wave.
4. Mild background slowing from the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports on a structural abnormality on the right
involving gray and white matter. The sharp waves support a localization-related
mechanism for epilepsy. The prior craniotomy would explain the breach rhythm and can
accentuate the epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Intra-hemispheric asymmetry with focal slowing on the right, arrhythmic delta
activity on the right. 2. Right mid to posterior temporal sharp wave. 3. Single right parietal sharp wave. 4. Mild background slowing from the left.

observed.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Significant background slowing. 2. Interhemispheric asymmetry with arrhythmic delta activity in the right hemisphere,

report:

MEDICATIONS: None

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record. This was a 1 hour study.


DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, a background EEG includes at 10 Hz, 50 microvolts, symmetric reactive posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity. Photic stimulation does elicit a driving response. Features of sleep include vertexes and posts.

HR: 72 bpm.

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This patient had a behavioral event during the EEG. Based on the technologist's notes, there was no impairment of awareness. In addition the characteristics of the movements were typical of a non-epileptic seizure with waxing and waning, movements in different planes and different directions as well as bilateral motor activity without impairment of awareness. A search for the underlying cause for these behaviors is advised.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG

report:

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is intubated but arousable.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates initially a very low voltage, suppressed pattern. At that point, the EEG demonstrates relatively low-voltage, featureless pattern.

There were portions of the record with relative suppression on one side or the other but there are also prominent bilateral features.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Low-voltage, relatively suppressed pattern at times. 2. Intermittently discontinuous pattern. 3. Shifting asymmetries with intermittent discontinuity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	88 year old woman with left craniotomy with subdural hematoma evacuation,  now for follow-up.

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Dilantin, Hydrochlorothiazide,  Lisinopril, Levothyroxine, Sotalol, Insulin, Lovenox.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1   channel EKG. Patient is intubated.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the record begins, a slow bilateral background of theta and delta activity is seen.  There is an interhemispheric asymmetry with some faster activity seen  in the right hemisphere. The background is suppressed.  In the left hemisphere arrhythmic sharp delta waves are seen with a huge field of spread. At times they stop and they start as the record continues, and at times they seem to go away. There is no evolution, but by the end of the record there is a question whether there would be more evolution in this left hemispheric sharp wave pattern as the record continued.

HR:	72 bpm


IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. 	Left hemisphere sharp waves.
2.	Slow background with slower frequencies in the left hemisphere.
3. 	Suppression of the background.


CLINICAL CORRELATION:   The slowing of the background is nonspecific but could be a result of severe cerebral dysfunction and the focal slowing could be a result of the structural abnormality from her history of a subdural hematoma. The continued left hemispheric sharp waves is consistent with an irrigative focus for epilepsy. At the end of the record there is a question whether there would be continuation and evolution of these sharp waves, which we do not see in this record.  Further clinical correlation is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Left hemisphere sharp waves. 2.Slow background with slower frequencies in the left hemisphere. 3. Suppression of the background.

activity.

regions.

generous field of spread in the C4, T 4, P4 regions. This epileptiform activity does not spread to
the contralateral size or evolve into seizure activity. This focus may be related to the patient's
known history of a temporal bleed on the right. Further clinical correlation is recommended.
IMPRESSION:

activity. 5. This epileptiform activity has a generous field of spread ranging from the C4, T 4 to P4
regions.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 78 year old male with expressive aphasia and confusion.

MEDICATIONS: None.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG includes a relatively low voltage pattern. There is a glimpse of a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. There is a prominent intrahemispheric asymmetry with some rhythmic slowing from the left mid temporal region and at times T1-T3 sharp waves. As the patient drifts off to sleep, some of these sharp waves are a bit more prominent at P3. The rhythmic slowing persists into stage 2 sleep and occurs as brief bursts but without definitive frequency evolution. During the prominent bursts of rhythmic slowing, testing is not performed and during the later section of the record there are trains of sharp waves noted in the record now at T5. Photic stimulation elicits driving response better represented on the right than the left, but present bilaterally. In the end of the record, which is when photic stimulation is seen the sharp waves are a bit more prominent at T5, T3.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Focal slowing in the left hemisphere most prominent in the temporal regions.
2. Sharp waves which may be prominent at T1, T3 or more posteriorly in the posterior temporal parietal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a structural abnormality in the left temporal region. Epileptiform activity is relatively wide spread in the temporal and parietal regions. Additional EEG recording in search of subclinical seizures may be appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Focal slowing in the left hemisphere most prominent in the temporal regions. 2. Sharp waves which may be prominent at T1, T3 or more posteriorly in the posterior temporal parietal region.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. There is photic stimulation but no hyperventilation.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the EEG is well organized, but when the patient becomes drowsy, the background demonstrates intermittent arrhythmic delta activity from the left temporal region. In addition, as the patient becomes drowsy intermittently, the alpha rhythm drops out much faster on the right compared to the left. What appears to be vertex waves are also accompanied by some right central temporal slowing and the vertex waves are consistently maximum on the right. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.

HR: 60 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Intermittent focal slowing on the left.
2. Asymmetric vertex waves which are maximum on the right.
3. An alpha asymmetry in drowsiness with drop out of the alpha rhythm earlier on the right compared to the left.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports pathology in either hemisphere. Although there were no epileptiform features, correlation with imaging is suggested. Typically, disrupted alpha would suggest pathology on the right and that would be supported by the focal right central temporal delta.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Intermittent focal slowing on the left. 2. Asymmetric vertex waves which are maximum on the right. 3. An alpha asymmetry in drowsiness with drop out of the alpha rhythm earlier on the right compared to the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:
The patient is a 37-year-old male with generalized tonic clonic seizures associated with loss of consciousness followed by
confusion. He was found down on the stairs. He has a past history of right frontal trauma.
MEDICATIONS:
Risperidone and Dilaudid.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:
This is an awake and drowsy record. In wakefulness, there is 9-10Hz posterior dominant rhythm bilaterally. The patient is
very drowsy and goes in and out of sleep during the recording. Drowsiness is characterized by generalized slowing. Stage
1 sleep is characterized by the presence of vertex waves. There were no epileptiform features noted. Hyperventilation did
not activate the record and there is no driving seen on photic stimulation.
Heart rate: 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:
Normal EEG in wakefulness to stage 2 sleep. No epileptiform features.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:
A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. If epilepsy is a clinical consideration, please consider
sleep-deprived study or a longer EEG recording to capture epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION Normal EEG in wakefulness to stage 2 sleep. No epileptiform features.

report:

I personally the EEG with the resident and reviewed the dictation. I agree with this report

report:
HISTORY:
A 42-year-old right-handed woman with epilepsy. She stopped her Dilantin two weeks ago and started drinking alcohol. She had three seizures in the emergency room on July 17 and received Ativan.
PAST HISTORY:
Asthma, epilepsy, stroke, bipolar disease, sickle cell disease and cocaine dependence.
MEDICINES:
Dilantin, Dilaudid, Ativan, Lovenox, Xanax, Benadryl and others.
INTRODUCTION:
Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG. Photic stimulation was performed. This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:
In maximum wakefulness there is generous beta. There are brief sections of the record with a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized by hypersynchronous rhythmic theta. there are minor asymmetries in the record. The photic driving response is slightly more vigorous on the left compared to the right and POSTS are more prominent on the left than the right. There is excess beta noted in wakefulness. Drowsiness is characterized by hypersynchronous slowing and beta.
Heart rate 72 BPM.
IMPRESSION:
This is a very mildly abnormal EEG due to a combination of asymmetric POSTS and asymmetric photic stimulation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:
While POSTS can be asymmetric, the asymmetric POSTS with the asymmetric photic suggests that there may be a
process, more likely in the right hemisphere than the left.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION This is a very mildly abnormal EEG due to a combination of asymmetric POSTS and asymmetric photic stimulation.

report:
HISTORY:
79-year-old woman with breast cancer admitted with urosepsis, found to have a right frontal infarct and recurrent seizures,
now poorly responsive but responsive.
INTRODUCTION:
Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of
EKG. The patient was intubated in the ICU. This is a bedside requested.
DESCRIPTION OF BACKGROUND:
Background EEG demonstrates a markedly abnormal pattern. On the left hemisphere, there is a continuous pattern with
a mixture of alpha and theta frequency activity. The right hemisphere demonstrates right frontal arrhythmic delta activity
with the polyspike component. Stimulation of the patient clearly produces an alerting response. Use of Ativan produces
background slowing and blunting of the PLED. Stimulation of the patient produces an arousal.
The epileptiform activity is high amplitude with a generous field of spread, but it has a very characteristic. Periodicity 0.8
Hz and does not evolve. With the use of Ativan, the epileptiform discharge decreases in amplitude, but the periodicity is
not affected. The use of Ativan does, however, produce slowing in the contralateral hemisphere.
Heart rate 120 BPM
IMPRESSION:
1 Abnormal EEG due to marked slowing in the right frontal region.
2. Periodic epileptiform activity 1n the right frontal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:
These findings are congruent with the patient's stroke. No clinical seizures were noted. The PLED'S represent an
epileptiform focus which may be a late ictal or post ictal sign. Because of th1s LTM was Initiated.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION 1 Abnormal EEG due to marked slowing in the right frontal region. 2. Periodic epileptiform activity 1n the right frontal region.

report:
INTRODUCTION:
PROCEDURE NOTE
Routine EEG performed using the standard 10/20 electrode placement system with additional EKG and anterior temporal
electrodes. No activation procedures were performed.

Intermittent T6 electrode artifact.
MEDICATIONS:
Protonix, insulin and p.r.n. labetalol.
HISTORY:
A 55-year-old male with hypertension and diabetes, noncompliant on medications with new brainstem and left cerebellar
hemorrhage.

The EEG opens to a diffusely slow background in the theta 5 to 7 Hz frequencies seen mainly over the frontal central
region, at times with an asymmetric appearance between the right and left hemispheres. There are intermittent periods of

stimulation with no clear change in the pattern.

Diffuse slow waves at 5 to 7 Hz and 20 to 70 microvolts.
SEIZURES:
IMPRESSION:
Abnormal EEG due to diffuse slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:
This EEG is consistent with diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology. No seizures or
epileptiform activity were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION Abnormal EEG due to diffuse slow waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 23 year old right handed male with microcephaly, history of anoxic brain injury, recurrent seizures. Last seizure was about a year ago. Recent hospitalization in June of 2011 for arrhythmia requiring defibrillator.  Transposition of great vessels.
MEDICATIONS:  Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.  The patient's stimulator discharged during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is generous frontocentral beta.  There is intermittent disruption of the alpha rhythm, particularly in the right occipital region.  This is quite infrequent.  Features of drowsiness include some bursts of hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing.  There are rare bursts of sharply contoured slowing in the left mid temporal region as well as rare, independent bursts on the right with a well-defined right T4 sharp wave noted during photic stimulation.  Photic stimulation also elicits a driving response.
HR:    60 bpm, with evidence of an active pacemaker discharge.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Intermittent disruption of the alpha rhythm, particularly on the right.
Bursts of somewhat irregular paroxysmal slowing in the transition to drowsiness.
Rare bursts of sharply contoured slowing which may be seen on the right or left.
Rare right temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG suggests a bihemispheric process.  Epileptiform activity was identified from the right, but there is also some suspicious activity on the left.  If additional information is needed, either a comparison with childhood EEGs or a follow-up sleep study may be of value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Intermittent disruption of the alpha rhythm, particularly on the right. Bursts of somewhat irregular paroxysmal slowing in the transition to drowsiness. Rare bursts of sharply contoured slowing which may be seen on the right or left. Rare right temporal sharp waves.

report:

Focal sharp waves seen frequently at C4, at times in rhythmic bursts but not clearly evolving in amplitude or frequency.
Focal slow waves seen at C4 at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 75 microvolts with an associated breach in this region.

Right central sharp waves.

report:

Following hyperventilation, as the patient drifts off to sleep, there is some shifting focal slowing with isolated theta or delta.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained. IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG age due to:
1. Background disorganization.
2. Slowing of the alpha rhythm.
3. Excess theta.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These are all mild to modest findings.  There were no epileptiform features.  Multiple medications may have contributed to the pattern
described above and a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.  A repeat study capturing more prolonged sleep may be helpful to identify epileptiform activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  56 year old right handed female with a history of hyperlipidemia, depression, hypothyroidism, and epilepsy with frequent seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Soma, Lamotrigine, Levothyroxine.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation and hyperventilation were performed.  The EEG was recorded only in wakefulness.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9 to 10 Hz which are reactive to eye opening.  There is a normal amount of frontocentral beta.  No sleep is captured.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation produce no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen at F7/T3 and F8/T4 frequently throughout the recording.
Focal slow waves seen also at F7/T3 and F8/T4, seen intermittently at a frequency of 2 to 4 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 40 microvolts.  During one period in the left anterior temporal region there was monomorphic discharge consistent with temporal intermittent rhythmic delta [TIRDA].
SEIZURES:   None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Bilateral anterior temporal sharp wave.
Focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with the diagnosis of localization related epilepsy, with seizures likely arising from either temporal lobe.  No seizures were captured.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Bilateral anterior temporal sharp wave. Focal slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  21 year old right handed woman with 2 episodes of loss of consciousness in October 2011.  She stood up, stretched, felt weak/lightheaded, and had motor movements of body with her head folding in.  These symptoms lasted 30 seconds.  She was disoriented afterward.
MEDICATIONS:  None.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  This was to have been a sleep-deprived EEG, but it was not.  It is a conventional 20-minute EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz 40 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm.  There is a small amount of low voltage frontocentral beta activity.  There are occasional hypersynchronous rhythmic discharges, compatible with hypnagogic hypersynchrony.  Hyperventilation was performed early in the record, producing a posterior predominant hyperventilation response.  In addition, there is some sharply contoured activity with a handful of sharp waves in the right centrotemporal and posterior temporal region noted in hyperventilation.  This was followed by a transition to sleep with brief attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Hypnagogic hypersynchrony characterizes the drowsy state.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
A posterior predominant hyperventilation response in an adult of this age.
The appearance of right central and posterior temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  If additional information is needed, a repeat study perhaps with physiological testing may be helpful to more completely understand the spells that this patient has been experiencing.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to A posterior predominant hyperventilation response in an adult of this age. The appearance of right central and posterior temporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:   67 year old woman with history of hypertension, thyroid and ovarian cancer, with an amnestic spell.
MEDICATIONS:  Atenolol, Zyrtec, Synthroid, Atorvastatin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity.  Lambda is noted. The patient is quite drowsy.  With eye closure she drifts into stage I sleep with prominent POSTS.  There is a bit of sustained eye movement in early sleep.  Vertex waves, K-complexes, spindles, and POSTS are noted.  Transitions in and out of sleep are observed.  There was no snoring noted.   Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.  There is one isolated slow wave burst on the left during hyperventilation. Photic stimulation is performed as the patient is transitioning in and out of stage II sleep.  Despite this, there is a driving response.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG for an adult of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were observed.  POSTS and lambda are normal phenomenon.  Rare snoring was noted.  Overall, the pattern
described above is compatible with a sleep deficit as might be anticipated in a sleep deprived EEG.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG for an adult of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  63 year old man with hypertension, alcohol abuse, and a fall overnight noted to have left thalamic hemorrhage.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Ativan, Metoprolol, Famotidine, Labetalol.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that is better seen over the right hemisphere and at best reaches 7 Hz and appears to be reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontal central beta seen mainly over the right hemisphere.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen in the left hemisphere maximum at T3 continuously throughout the recording.
Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz seen during wakefulness.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1.  Left hemispheric slowing maximal in the anterior temporal region.
2.  Mild generalized slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal structural dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region which is consistent with a known hemorrhage.  In addition, there is evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology and may be due, at least in part, to medication effect.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to 1.  Left hemispheric slowing maximal in the anterior temporal region. 2.  Mild generalized slow waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  57 year old female presents with history of MCA stroke now with continuous left hand shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Oxycodone, Donepezil, ASA, Gabapentin, Escitalopram, Clonidine, Prochlorperazine
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This is an awake and drowsy record.  The patient has right arm and hand pain during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat disorganized with generous beta, but a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is a subtle asymmetry between the 2 hemispheres with disruption of faster frequency activity which is relatively subtle, but is seen in the frontocentral and posterotemporal regions.  In addition, as the patient becomes drowsy there is a bit more focal slowing with isolated delta or theta.
Features of photic stimulation include a driving response which is better seen on the right compared to the left.
HR:    120 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Mild generalized background slowing.
Focal slowing with disruption of faster frequency activity in the hemisphere and intermittent focal delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The patient's symptoms of twitching in the left hand were not associated with sharp waves or spikes.  This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function as well as a focal process as might be considered following a stroke.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Mild generalized background slowing. Focal slowing with disruption of faster frequency activity in the hemisphere and intermittent focal delta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:   61 year old man with history of CAD, CABG in 1995, COPD, hepatitis B virus, bilateral PEs, hypertension, who presents with respiratory failure and altered mental status.
MEDICATIONS:  Zosyn, vancomycin
REASON FOR STUDY:  Altered mental status.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while unresponsive.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 6 Hz, which does not appear to be reactive to eye opening.  There is not a normal amount of frontal central beta.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.  No activating procedures were performed.
During the recording the patient is stimulated, but there appears to be no clear change in the record.  At times intermittently there is periods of faster frequencies coming through the background, but this does not appear to be due to stimulation and it just occurs for seconds.  It may represent arousal.  Overall the background is also consistent with some abnormal discharges, which I will discuss in the next paragraph.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-70 mV.  In addition, there is intermittent triphasic waves seen throughout the recording.
There is also some sharply contoured transient that are maximal in the midline prefrontal, as well as vertex region.  However, this has more of a metabolic/triphasic morphology and does not appear to be epileptic.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
generalized slowing and triphasics.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  However, the presence of triphasics suggests a metabolic component to this encephalopathy.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to generalized slowing and triphasics.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  58 year old man, presents after found down with no vital signs, status post PEA code with resuscitation after 15 minutes.
MEDICATIONS:  Propofol and Zosyn
REASON FOR STUDY:  Status post code, unresponsiveness.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while unresponsive.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely abnormal background with no posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  The record is basically comprised of generalized periodic epileptiform discharges with a maximum frontal negativity seen at times slightly more on the left than the right at a frequency of 2.5-3 Hz with an amplitude of 20-70 microvolts occurring continuously throughout the recording.  At times, there is intermixed polyspike seen in the small bursts of 400 msec to 1 second.  Throughout the recording, there appears to be no clinical correlate to these generalized periodic epileptiform discharges.  The patient is stimulated during the recording and there is no change in this pattern.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized periodic epileptiform discharges (GPEDs) seen continuously throughout the recording with intermittent anterior predominant polyspikes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cortical dysfunction and irritability, which is consistent with the known hypoxic injury.  No seizures were clearly seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Generalized periodic epileptiform discharges (GPEDs) seen continuously throughout the recording with intermittent anterior predominant polyspikes.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  36 year old woman with multiple sclerosis and epilepsy, admitted with recurrent tonic-clonic seizures and postictal confusion, initial presentation in status epilepticus requiring Dilantin load.  Seizures characterized by head turning to the right, then left arm shaking which progresses into a tonic-clonic seizure.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Vimpat, Topamax.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This EEG demonstrates a slow pattern, rich in beta.  Frequent eye blink artifact is noted.  A discrete sharp wave is noted in the right temporal region.  It has a variable field and can include T2 and T4.
HR:    96 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Excess beta.
Excess delta, particularly frontal delta.
Modest shifting delta in an awake patient who is on the phone.
Tiny, discrete temporal sharp waves noted only in the initial sections of the record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These very small polyspike discharges at T2 and T4 suggest a cortical process.  They were only seen in the beginning of the EEG.  The generalized background slowing and bursts of beta and delta may be part of the postictal state or medications used for the status epilepticus.  The markedly slow
background in an awake, conversant patient does, however, suggest a chronic encephalopathy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Excess beta. Excess delta, particularly frontal delta. Modest shifting delta in an awake patient who is on the phone. Tiny, discrete temporal sharp waves noted only in the initial sections of the record.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  42 year old right handed woman with life long migraine headaches, now with an early morning headache with lightheadedness and dry mouth, but without visual phenomenon.  In addition, the patient has complex migraine, which begins as an aura of a bad smell, bad taste, then headache with nausea, vomiting, photophobia, and phonophobia.  Previous MRI scan of the brain was normal.  Severe insomnia.
MEDICATIONS:  Topamax, Elavil
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Mu activity, as well as lambda was identified. The patient appears to be very sleepy, transitions in and out of stage II sleep.  Spindle activity is noted.  There seem to be fragments of sleep spindles just as she is dropping almost in and out wakefulness.  As the sleep record continues, more abundant stage II sleep is identified, but in the transition in and out of stage II sleep, there are fragments of early drowsiness, almost emerging into a stage II sleep pattern. The patient is awakened at the end of the test and answers complex questions. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:   66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Somewhat unusual, but normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are no epileptiform features, but there are multiple normal variants, including mu and rhythmic temporal theta of drowsiness. Given the transitions noted early in the record between wakefulness and stage II sleep, an underlying sleep deficit may account for this.  If there is any other question, a follow up study when the patient has had adequate sleep may be of value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Somewhat unusual, but normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 22-year-old with gunshot injury to the left side of the head at age 10, epilepsy began at age 18 with 2 seizures every 9 months. The patient was involved in a motor vehicle accident in 2010, now having frequent seizures characterized by incontinence and postictal confusion. Seizures occur out of sleep.
MEDICATIONS:  Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm which is identified bilaterally.  There is a prominent breach rhythm identified with accentuation of amplitude of activity in the left central region as well as underlying arrhythmic delta activity in that same region.  Despite some head rocking artifact and the breach, as the patient becomes drowsy a left central sharp wave emerges from that region, again with accentuation of the breach.  Drowsiness is also characterized by an increase in beta followed by vertex waves.  The patient transitions in and out of sleep.
Hyperventilation produces an increase in both generalized slowing as well as accentuating the focal slowing from the left and to some extent the sharp wave in the left central region.
Photic stimulation was performed as the patient is transitioning in and out of sleep.  A driving response was identified.
Heart rate 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal electroencephalography due to:
Continue with focal slowing in the left central region.
Despite a breach rhythm, a defined left central sharp wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a structural or functional process on the left involving grey and white matter.  The sharp waves identified were also in the same region as the skull defect.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal electroencephalography due to Continue with focal slowing in the left central region. Despite a breach rhythm, a defined left central sharp wave.

report:
LENGTH OF RECORDING:  22 minutes
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is an 83-year-old woman with history of Alzheimer's disease, coronary artery disease, chronic kidney disease, and others, now presents with change in mental status.
MEDICATIONS:  Current medications include donepezil, isosorbide, Pravachol, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  Condition of the recording:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead placement.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a low-amplitude 9 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  Anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient is weak.  No clear sleep architecture is present. Intermittent polymorphic theta and delta activity are captured over the left temporal region.  Hyperventilation is not performed. Stepped photic stimulation results in no additional abnormalities.
FINDINGS:
Mild background disorganization.
Intermittent mild left temporal slowing.
No stage 2 sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake-only 22-minute electroencephalogram due to mild background disorganization and mild intermittent left temporal slowing.  Mild background slowing indicates etiologically nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  Focal left temporal slowing indicates a possible underlying structural lesion, and in this case, could be consistent with patient history of Alzheimer's type dementia.  No epileptiform discharges were captured; however, stage 2 sleep was not recorded. If clinical indication for seizures persist, a repeat study with stage 2 sleep may be of benefit.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake-only 22-minute electroencephalogram due to mild background disorganization and mild intermittent left temporal slowing.  Mild background slowing indicates etiologically nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  Focal left temporal slowing indicates a possible underlying structural lesion, and in this case, could be consistent with patient history of Alzheimer's type dementia.  No epileptiform discharges were captured; however, stage 2 sleep was not recorded. If clinical indication for seizures persist, a repeat study with stage 2 sleep may be of benefit

report:

The sharply contoured slowing on the left may be correlated with underlying changes in the left hemisphere.  Hypersomnolence noted may be due to postictal state or medications.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 65-year-old woman, found down with transient left hemiparesis, transient hypoglycemia and transient hypotension, now more awake and alert. Still intubated. CT scan negative for stroke.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, many others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was intubated and somewhat agitated.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This is a technically challenging EEG.  There was significant muscle and motion artifact in an otherwise low-voltage pattern.  On rare occasion, there was a glimpse of an alpha rhythm and when the muscle artifact drops out, there is significant beta.  Toward the close of the record, there is a decrease in muscle artifact, and there is a suggestion of asymmetry with perhaps a bit more delta in the right central region than the left.
Heart rate is 110 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is a technically challenging but abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background with a low-voltage primarily beta pattern.
A question of a subtle asymmetry in the right hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified; however, there is a challenging EEG because of the degree of muscle artifact.  A followup study in the lab, after the patient has been extubated and is cooperative, is suggested if there is concern regarding seizures.  There is questionable slowing on the right which may be correlated with additional imaging.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a technically challenging but abnormal EEG due to Replacement of normal background with a low-voltage primarily beta pattern. A question of a subtle asymmetry in the right hemisphere.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 67-year-old female with history of epilepsy and depression who presents for followup.  Her last seizure was more than 2 years ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin and Seroquel.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm was 9-9.5 Hz in frequency seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is 7-7.5 Hz diffuse theta activity seen during wakefulness, which is distributed symmetrically.  There is presence of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Drowsiness was characterized by disappearance of the posterior dominant rhythm and slowing of the background and absence of muscle and eye blink artifacts.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and did not result in a driving response.  Heart rate was 70 beats per minute with arrhythmia.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to diffuse slowing of the background with theta activity seen during wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings could be due to toxic, metabolic, hypoxic, or infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to the effect of sedating medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunction or degenerative brain disease.  The general clinical correlation was recommended.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures are identified in this record.  Note that the patient has arrhythmia.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to diffuse slowing of the background with theta activity seen during wakefulness.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Left arm shaking without change in mental status.

Stage I and stage II sleep was captured.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
Abnormal discharges:
Continuous C4/T4 slowing in the 2 to 4 Hz frequency and 20 to 40 microvolt amplitude range with an additional increased amplitude and frequency which is indicative of breach in that region.
Intermittent independent T3 slowing.
Excess theta in wakefulness.

Continuous right centrotemporal slowing.
Intermittent independent left mid-temporal slowing.

report:

Intermittent mild left temporal slowing.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and asleep 1 hour EEG due to intermittent mild left temporal slowing.  This finding indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, possibly structural in etiology.  The lack of epileptiform discharges in the routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

report:
LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  26 minutes.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Both hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
HISTORY:  The patient is a 22-year-old woman who is 13 weeks' pregnant.  While in the emergency room she was observed to have seizure-like activity lasting approximately 2 minutes.  This occurred twice.  The patient was aware but was unable to speak.
PAST MEDICAL HISTORY:  Notable for chronic gastritis, gastric ulcers, asthma, kidney stones and panic attacks.
CURRENT MEDICATION:  Zofran.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed modulated moderate amplitude 2.5 Hz alpha activity.  Voltages of posterior dominant rhythm are higher over the right hemisphere by approximately 50%.  During sleep, symmetrical vertex waves, sleep spindles and K complexes are captured.  Prominent POSTS (positive single sharp transients of sleep) are captured primarily over the right hemisphere.  Additionally, epochs similar to REM sleep are observed as well.  During those epochs, bursts of alpha activity is captured over the posterior leads, primarily over the right hemisphere only.  Hyperventilation does not result in change in the background.  Photic stimulation results in asymmetrical driving at low frequencies with occipital driving observed only over the right hemisphere.
FINDINGS:
Voltage asymmetry of the posterior dominant rhythm, with voltages higher over the right by approximately 50%.
Prominent POSTS over the right hemisphere.
Occipital driving observed over the right only at the low voltage frequencies.
__________ REM sleep captured, __________ sleep captured.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and asleep 26-minute EEG due to asymmetry of occipital alpha rhythm voltages, with higher voltages over the right hemisphere by approximately 50%, as well as occipital driving observed at the lower frequencies only over the right hemisphere.  These findings suggest focal cerebral dysfunction over the left posterior region.  Additionally, capturing of REM-oriented sleep during routine EEG is unusual and clinical correlation of an underlying sleep disorder is suggested.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and asleep 26-minute EEG due to asymmetry of occipital alpha rhythm voltages, with higher voltages over the right hemisphere by approximately 50%, as well as occipital driving observed at the lower frequencies only over the right hemisphere.  These findings suggest focal cerebral dysfunction over the left posterior region.  Additionally, capturing of REM-oriented sleep during routine EEG is unusual and clinical correlation of an underlying sleep disorder is suggested

report:

Moderate diffuse slowing.
Periods of discontinuity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 58-year-old man with a known history of seizures, who presents with a prolonged generalized clonic-tonic convulsion.
MEDICATIONS:  Ativan, propofol, and others.
CONDITIONS OF THE RECORDING:  The recording is performed according to the standard 10/20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.  The recording was reviewed intermittently by the attending physician throughout the recording.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The background consists of low amplitude, diffuse beta activity, very diffuse fast activity in the beta frequency range admixed with periods of a background of discontinuity.  With stimulation, the background becomes continuous and voltages increase somewhat.  There appears to be a paucity of faster frequencies over the right temporal region.  No normal sleep architecture is captured.  No electrographic seizures are observed.
FINDINGS:
Moderate to severe diffuse background slowing with periods of discontinuity.
Reactivity present.
Paucity of faster frequencies over the right temporal region.
No electrographic seizures.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal approximately 13 hour continuous video EEG monitoring due to moderate background slowing and focal right temporal slowing.  Diffuse background slowing indicates etiologically nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction, and in this case likely at least partially related to medication effect.  Focal right temporal slowing indicates focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural in etiology and is consistent with the patient's history of prior right MCA stroke.  Diffuse beta could be secondary to medication effect such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.  No electrographic seizures were captured.  These findings were conveyed to the primary neurology team.

report:

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 7.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with generous background theta.

They ranged from a high amplitude 70 microvolt  T1 sharp waves to more discreet left anterior temporal sharp waves with variable maximum.  On 1 occasion, there is a phase reversal in the referential montage between T1 and F7.  One of these discharges also seems to have more of a left frontocentral localization.
Heart rate 60 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Left anterior temporal sharp waves noted in drowsiness.
Excess theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is the 4th EEG for this patient.  Only 1 prior EEG identified the left temporal sharp waves, but prior EEGs did identify the excess background theta.  This EEG supports a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to Left anterior temporal sharp waves noted in drowsiness. Excess theta.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 70-year-old woman with recurrent tonic-clonic seizures from 2 o'clock this afternoon, transferred from Episcopal Hospital.  Patient has not returned to baseline mental status, not speaking well, confused, evaluated for subclinical status epilepticus.

MEDICATIONS:  Versed, others, phenytoin.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the neuro ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1-channel EKG.  This is a technically very challenging EEG in an uncooperative patient.  The EEG captures the awake and agitated state.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the initial sections of the record, the patient is awake and moving about.  The overall background is quite disorganized.  Head rocking artifact is noted, but there was also an increase in amplitude in the right scalp electrodes particularly the right temporal regions.  When the patient is a bit more cooperative, is a bit more theta.  The nurses attempt to console the patient with little success.  At some point, there is an increase in beta as the patient's Versed starts to take effect and the patient started snoring.  As she does so, a more restricted area of focal slowing in the right posterior quadrant was noted and there are discernible, right occipitotemporal sharp waves noted.  The sedation does not last long and the patient is quickly agitated again.  The pattern from the left is also disorganized, but lacks the same quantity of arrhythmic delta activity.  The sharp waves are irregular with a variable maximum and can include T4 or O2.

Heart rate N/A.

IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging, but abnormal EEG due to:
1. Sharp waves from the right hemisphere, typically posterior temporal, but not exclusively occipital or posterior temporal, sometimes mid temporal.
2. Arrhythmic delta activity, right posterior quadrant.
3. Background slowing and disorganization from both hemispheres.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures were recorded.  This EEG supports a structural process on the right involving gray and white matter as well as a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy.  Additional recording may be considered if the patient suffers additional seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Technically challenging, but abnormal EEG due to 1. Sharp waves from the right hemisphere, typically posterior temporal, but not exclusively occipital or posterior temporal, sometimes mid temporal. 2. Arrhythmic delta activity, right posterior quadrant. 3. Background slowing and disorganization from both hemispheres.

report:
:
History:	76 year old woman found unresponsive yesterday.  She was found to have PEA.
Diffuse body jerks were noted this am.
Medications:	Depakote, Propofol at 20, Vecuronium 8 mg total during the study
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Extended, 40-60 min, portable
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, comatose
Description:
There is no PDR and no AP gradient.  The background consists of a mixture of polymorphic
theta<<delta activity and diffuse frontally predominant polyspikes.  As the recording opens,
polyspikes are low in amplitude and infrequent. As the recording progresses,  they gradually
increase in frequency, amplitude and duration.  Clinically, they are associated with diffuse body
jerks.  Four brief (~20 seconds) clinical and electrographic seizures are captured.  Clinically patient
has diffuse body jerks that rapidly evolve into rhythmic clonic movements of upper extremities.
Patient is given vecuronium at the time of the last seizure, so no movement is identified with that
event.  Electrographically, the first 3 seizures are characterized by diffuse EMG artifact. Patient is
paralyzed at the time of the fourth seizure.  That seizure starts with moderate amplitude diffuse
polyspikes that evolve into a mixture of diffuse 8-10 Hz  activity with underriding low amplitude fast
activity.  At the end of the seizures, rhythmic ~ 3 Hz diffuse delta activity is seen accompanied by
the underriding fast activity.  After each seizure, frequency, duration and amplitude of polyspikes
decrease dramatically.
Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  There is no change in the background
activity to visual, auditory, tactile, or noxious stimuli.
Summary of Findings:
Seizure, few, ~20 second each, generalized
Polyspikes, abundant diffuse
No reactivity
Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, severe
Interpretation:
This is a very abnormal 1 hour EEG in a comatose patient due to severe diffuse slowing, lack of
reactivity, frequent diffuse epileptiform discharges (clinically associated with generalized body jerks)
and 4 brief generalized seizures. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of marked
diffuse cerebral dysfunction and profound cortical excitability and in a patient with post-anoxic
brain injury indicate low likelihood of full neurological recovery.  These findings were conveyed to
the neurology consult team and to the primary team at the time of the recording.  Patient will be
placed on a long-term EEG monitoring.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is a very abnormal 1 hour EEG in a comatose patient due to severe diffuse slowing, lack of
reactivity, frequent diffuse epileptiform discharges (clinically associated with generalized body jerks)
and 4 brief generalized seizures. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of marked
diffuse cerebral dysfunction and profound cortical excitability and in a patient with post-anoxic
brain injury indicate low likelihood of full neurological recovery.  These findings were conveyed to
the neurology consult team and to the primary team at the time of the recording.  Patient will be
placed on a long-term EEG monitoring

report:

MEDICATIONS:  Heparin and aspirin.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This is a technically adequate study.  Hyperventilation was not possible, but photic stimulation was completed.  The patient was quite somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  The abnormalities include an asymmetry between the 2 hemispheres.  The left hemisphere is higher amplitude and the right hemisphere is lower voltage and more suppressed.  There are bursts of rhythmic, generalized delta.  In addition, there are bursts of more focal delta, maximum in the left frontal region.  Some of the left frontal delta somewhat sharply contoured.  An intermittent alpha rhythm of 7 hertz emerges.
The patient is somewhat confused, but answers questions with some detail, although some of the details are incorrect.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in bursts of rhythmic delta.
Photic stimulation did not significantly activate the record.
Heart rate 78 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This EEG identifies multiple abnormalities including:
Bursts of frontal delta.
An amplitude asymmetry with a lower voltage, somewhat slower record on the right.
Left frontocentral higher amplitude, rhythmic delta, which is at times sharply contoured.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a bihemispheric process.  There may be multiple contributors including a toxic or metabolic component, and/or bihemispheric structural components.  Correlation with imaging and clinical examination is suggested.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This EEG identifies multiple abnormalities including Bursts of frontal delta. An amplitude asymmetry with a lower voltage, somewhat slower record on the right. Left frontocentral higher amplitude, rhythmic delta, which is at times sharply contoured.

report:

MEDICATIONS:  unknown
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 10.5 hertz, 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements with an increase in theta.  Head rocking artifact was noted in drowsiness, hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.  Photic stimulation did elicit a driving response.
Heart rate 50 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness with bradycardia.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  If additional information is needed, a more prolonged study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness with bradycardia.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 52-year-old woman, status post aortic dissection repair on Sunday, 03/08/2015, for emergent dissection.  Subsequently found to have a massive right hemiparesis with smaller strokes on the left.  Intubated, but responsive.
MEDICATIONS:  Morphine, nicardipine, Lasix, fentanyl, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed at bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system with one channel EKG.  The patient is intubated, but responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Background EEG is markedly abnormal, but demonstrates a continuous pattern.  The overall pattern is relatively suppressed from the right hemisphere with smaller amounts of alpha and theta frequency activity.  From the left hemisphere, arrhythmic delta activity was noted with occasional sharp waves noted in the left hemisphere including left mid temporal or central regions.  These are medium amplitude sharp waves.  There is also a small amount of wicket noted from the left.  This record does capture some drowsiness with an increase in beta frequency activity.  When the patient is more active, there is a bit more muscle noted.
Heart rate:  98 BPM to 112 BPM, faster heart rate when the patient is a little bit more active.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due:
Generalized background slowing.
An asymmetry with significant disruption of faster frequency activity on the right.
Intermittent attenuations noted, which are asymmetric, more remarkable from the right.
Occasional sharp waves noted from the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function affecting both gray and white matter, but more significantly involving the right hemisphere with more significant disruption of activity from the right.  The sharp waves are relatively blunted in nature, but in this individual with bihemispheric stroke, raise some potential for seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due Generalized background slowing. An asymmetry with significant disruption of faster frequency activity on the right. Intermittent attenuations noted, which are asymmetric, more remarkable from the right. Occasional sharp waves noted from the left.

report:

report:
﻿History:	31 year old woman who had several seizures in 5/2014.  Large left frontal
meningioma was subsequently found and patient underwent tumor resection.  She
has occasional seizures since then.
Medications:	Tegretol
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 11Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  Diffuse excess beta activity is present.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha
rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely, followed by a few vertex waves.  Vertex
waves are more pronounced over the left.
Occasional polymorphic delta activity is noted over the left frontotemporal region.  Additional,
moderate amplitude fast activity is present over the bilateral frontocentral regions (breach artifact),
left>right.  A single left frontotemporal sharp transient is captured.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with fair cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at
multiple flash rates.  A single EKG lead demonstrates heart rate <60 bpm.
Summary of Findings:
No stage 2 sleep
Breach artifact, bilateral, frontocentral
Beta, excessive
Sharp transients, one, left frontotemporal
Focal slowing, polymorphic, occasional, moderate, left frontotemporal
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 28 minute EEG due to occasional moderate left
frontotemporal focal slowing.  This finding is indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is
etiologically non-specific, but possibly structural in origin.  Breach artifact is secondary to the
underlying skull defect.  The presence of a single left frontotemporal sharp transient waveform is of
uncertain clinical significance.  It occurs in the same location as breach artifact and focal slowing.
The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of
epilepsy.  Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 28 minute EEG due to occasional moderate left
frontotemporal focal slowing.  This finding is indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is
etiologically non-specific, but possibly structural in origin.  Breach artifact is secondary to the
underlying skull defect.  The presence of a single left frontotemporal sharp transient waveform is of
uncertain clinical significance.  It occurs in the same location as breach artifact and focal slowing

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 38-year-old man with childhood head trauma and development of epilepsy as an young adult. 5 year history of  Complex partial seizures followed by tonic-clonic seizures 5 years ago.  Current seizure frequency, unknown, intermittent dizziness.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This was a technically acceptable EEG with impedances below 5 kilohms with the exception of the T1-T2 electrodes.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the EEG is well organized.  There is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Somewhat irregular mixed theta delta was noted in the frontal central regions. It is present bilaterally, but is somewhat more prominent in the right hemisphere.
Hyperventilation was performed early on in the record and very quickly produces a feeling in the patient of dizziness and jitteriness.  Bursts of frontal theta are noted, somewhat irregular and a little bit more prominent on the right in hyperventilation.  Photic stimulation was performed immediately after hyperventilation, in the early parts of the record and did elicit a driving response.  The patient remained quite anxious and there is a great deal of muscle artifact noted in the background.  In this challenging EEG with a great deal of muscle artifact, there appears to be an underlying 4 hertz spike and wave complex, typically seen in the right hemisphere sometimes with a bihemispheric predominance.  Review of the video identifies no twitching of the patient during the discharges.
Heart rate:  66 bpm.  Frequent PVCs.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Intermittent rhythmic somewhat irregular theta delta noted in relaxed wakefulness, and somewhat accentuated by hyperventilation.
In this technically challenging EEG, likely an underlying spike and wave complex seen a bit more prominently in the right hemisphere, but sometimes of bilateral representation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In comparison to a previous study 5 years ago, the patient had 3-5 hertz frontally predominant spike and wave activity as well as right frontal spike and wave activity and right
focal slowing.  Because of the degree of muscle artifact, these findings are not as well identified.  Additional evaluation of the patient regarding the tremulousness and PVCs may be of value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to Intermittent rhythmic somewhat irregular theta delta noted in relaxed wakefulness, and somewhat accentuated by hyperventilation. In this technically challenging EEG, likely an underlying spike and wave complex seen a bit more prominently in the right hemisphere, but sometimes of bilateral representation.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 60-year-old male found down on


December 14th with traumatic intracerebral hemorrhage, skull

fracture, went on to have right craniotomy.  Left frontal EVD.

Now, with right upper gaze deviation.



MEDICATIONS:  Keppra. No others listed.



INTRODUCTION:  Twenty four minute digital video EEG was performed

at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement

with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient was intubated, but was


examined during the EEG.  There was no record of the use of

sedative, hypnotic medications in the report provided by the

technologist.



DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG demonstrates a medium

amplitude pattern with a mixed frequency pattern.  There are


lower voltage theta and delta frequency activity.  Intermittent,




subtle attenuations were noted, with attenuation or at least a

decrease in amplitude of the background.  These effects last 1 to


3 seconds and are not entirely a burst suppression pattern.  In

the sections of the record with more vigorous cerebral activity,


there is right frontal delta.  There is also a lower voltage

right frontal fast wave or lower voltage frontal sharp wave noted

intermittently.  Rare left frontal sharp waves were also noted.

Tactile stimulation of the patient seem to produce an attenuation


of cerebral activity lasting 7 seconds in duration.



Heart rate 144 bpm.


IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:

1. A low voltage slow pattern.


2. Intermittent attenuation of the background.

3. The phenomenon of attenuation of the background with tactile


stimulation.

4. Intermittent sharp waves noted from either frontal region,

right greater than left.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No seizures were recorded.  The

epileptiform features noted were in the region of the previous


cranial defect and may have been accentuated by that fact.  In

the absence of the use of sedative, hypnotic medications, the

background described above is a worrisome pattern.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to 
1. A low voltage slow pattern. 

2. Intermittent attenuation of the background. 
3. The phenomenon of attenuation of the background with tactile


stimulation. 
4. Intermittent sharp waves noted from either frontal region,

right greater than left.

TECHNIQUE:

A bedside  ICU Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the
International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a
technically satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG and  Verbal stimulation.  The
patient has a bone flap.




EEG BACKGROUND:




The waking background is abnormal.  The patient is awake, with eye opening and on the left there is
an organized  mixture of theta  alpha and beta frequencies, with a symmetric and reactive 7-9 Hertz
posterior dominant rhythm (PDR). The normal anterior-to-posterior gradient of frequency and
amplitude is present.



The right hemisphere demonstrates marked reduction in faster frequency with more of a delta/theta
featureless pattern.  Superimposed on this is R frontocentral breech with higher amplitude R F4-C4
delta activity and focal sharp waves F4 maximum.  There is intermittent beta accentuation in the
region of the breach.




There is muscle twitch artifact noted on the left, seen at times diffusely from left temporal scalp
electrodes and intermittently as a focal twitch. The isolated twitches lack consistent link to the R
frontal sharps.




Right  focal slowing is present.


EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:


See above


OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None


ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:


Auditory and tactile stimulation do not activate the records


EVENTS:


Focal facial twitch without consistent EEG correlate


HEART RATE:


A heart rate of 100 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.


IMPRESSION:


This is an abnormal ICU routine EEG due to:

1. Continuous R focal slowing.

2. In the context of R sided breech rhythm, R frontal focal slowing and intermittent sharp waves


CLINICAL CORRELATION:


These findings must be interpreted in the clinical context of the patient's motor activity and imaging.
While no electrographic seizures were defined by this study, the possibility of epilepsy partialis is not
excluded by this study.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 

This is an abnormal ICU routine EEG due to 
1. Continuous R focal slowing. 
2. In the context of R sided breech rhythm, R frontal focal slowing and intermittent sharp waves

seizures.

TECHNIQUE:








A bedside Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the
International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a
technically  satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG. this EEG is notable for an
nervous-appearing patient with excessive amounts of muscle and beta




EEG BACKGROUND:


The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a moderate amount of bifrontal beta
activity, with scant alpha organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is
characterized very little  reactive posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which attenuates symmetrically
with eye opening, but appears to be in the beta frequency range.


During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse beta are seen.


Sleep is not sustained

EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:


No epileptiform activity is present.


OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None
