IMPRESSION:


This is an unsual but normal bedside routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:

Generous beta may be correlated with patient's clinical history and exposure to medications.  The
absence of an alpha rhythm is not strictly speaking pathological, particularly if there are no other
abnormal findings.


This EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.  Given the limitations, please request
an EEG in the lab of 20-60 minutes in duration

IMPRESSION

A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically  satisfactory
record and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.  Patient seems to be
excessively drowsy



EEG BACKGROUND:

In maximal wakefulness  waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha
and a moderate amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior
gradient.  Wakefulness is characterized by a symmetric and reactive 9 Hertz posterior dominant
rhythm (PDR), which attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.





During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.  There are multiple epochs with early
drowsiness with slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm to approximately 7 Hz.  Additional features
of drowsiness including shifting slowing, more notably within bit more focal slowing on the left.
Additionally, very early in drowsiness, bursts of rhythmic frontal high amplitude delta 3-4 seconds
duration were noted






Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with POSTS synchronous and symmetric vertex
waves, sleep spindles and K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.



No generalized slowing is present. Shifting  focal slowing is present. L>R


EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:


No epileptiform activity is present.


OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


Sharply contoured delta is noted in the left mid temporal region in drowsiness on rare occasions

per second (fps) does not produce any EEG changes.

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.

A heart rate of  60 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.

This is an abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG for an adult of this age, who also appears to be
excessively drowsy


1. FIRDA

2. Shifting slowing R<L with sharply contoured slowing left temporal

CLINICAL CORRELATION:


This routine EEG can be correlated with imaging and clinical features.  Given the complaint of
memory loss, the research from metabolic cause, as well as a disorder of hypersomnolence may be
appropriate correlation with imaging, in regard to the shifting slowing may also be of value.


A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.

IMPRESSION

report:
HISTORY: 48 y.o. Male- yesterday 9/21 at 11 am he coded on the floor, rhythm was asystole and then V tach for at least 30 minutes with multiple rounds of epinephrine. After ROSC patient required 3 pressors. Cardiology was called and they did a bedside echo that showed a dilated RV with strain which was accounted to a possible massive Pulmonary Embolism. He was never on sedation. Not hypothermic but BP 70/40 with multiple pressors.   Primary team noted absence of gag and corneal reflex and asked for the brain dead exam referred for routine EEG for brain death evaluation.  

MEDICATIONS: Current Facility-Administered Medications: phenylephrine (NEO-SYNEPHRINE) 80 mg in sodium chloride 0.9 % 250 mL infusion potassium chloride IVPB 20 mEq 100 mL potassium chloride IVPB 20 mEq 100 mL potassium phosphate 30 mmol in dextrose 5 % in water 250 mL IVPB pantoprazole (PROTONIX) injection 40 mg insulin lispro (HumaLOG) injection 1-5 Units heparin 25,000 units (100 units/mL) in 0.45% sodium chloride 250 mL infusion (Premix) potassium chloride IVPB 20 mEq 100 mL magnesium sulfate IVPB 4 g 100 mL HYDROmorphone (DILAUDID) 1 mg/mL PCA infusion 50 mL And naloxone (NARCAN) injection 0.4 mg vasopressin (PITRESSIN) 100 Units in dextrose 5 % in water 250 mL infusion sodium bicarbonate injection 100 mEq norepinephrine (LEVOPHED) 16 mg/250 mL (64 mcg/mL) in NSS infusion EPINEPHrine (ADRENALIN) 4 mg in dextrose 5 % in water 250 mL infusion niCARdipine (CARDENE) 20 mg in NaCl (iso-os) 200 mL infusion vancomycin (VANCOCIN) 1,000 mg in sodium chloride 0.9 % 250 mL IVPB MB+ piperacillin-tazobactam (ZOSYN) 3.375 g in sodium chloride 0.9 % 50 mL IVPB MB+ DOBUTamine (DOBUTREX) 500 mg in dextrose 5 % water 250 mL infusion hydrocortisone sod succ (PF) (Solu-CORTEF) injection 100 mg morphine injection 1 mg 

SEDATION: None 

TECHNIQUE: A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG and Tactile/ Verbal stimulation. This standard ECS montage was used for 30 minutes. Tactile and verbal stimulation were performed, and the technologist confirm the integrity of the system  

EEG BACKGROUND: The background is suppressed. No cerebral activity was identified 

EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY: None  

OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):  None  

ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: There is no change to visual, auditory, tactile, or noxious stimuli. 

EVENTS: There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.  

HEART RATE: A heart rate of 104 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.  

IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal 50 minute ICUEEG due to: 1. Absence of cerebral activity 

CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings, recorded >24 hours after cardiac arrest, in the absence of the use of sedative hypnotic medications or hypothermia support a severe disturbance of cerebral function. This EEG demonstrates electrocerebral inactivity (ECS). Correlation with overall clinical picture is advised.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: This is an abnormal 50 minute ICUEEG due to: 1. Absence of cerebral activity

TECHNIQUE:




A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG, hyperventilation, and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is characterized by the presence of fairly generalized poorly organized
medium amplitude 5-6 Hz activity with intermixed irregular delta frequency slowing and
superimposed muscle artifact. Occasional runs of medium to high amplitude irregular delta activity
and anteriorly predominant triphasiform discharges were seen during periods of increased drowsiness.
Occasional sharp-and slow-wave discharges were seen in the right frontotemporal region at T4-F8
and infrequent low amplitude sharp transients were also seen at P3.





Sleep is not captured



No focal slowing is present.



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:


Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180 seconds with good cooperation and produces
no effect.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce
any EEG changes.



EVENTS:


There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.


HEART RATE:


A heart rate of 62 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.


IMPRESSION:


This is an abnormal awake and drowsy 1 hour EEG due to:

1. Diffuse background slowing and disorganization

2. Occasional runs of triphasiform activity during drowsiness.


3. Right frontotemporal sharp-slow wave discharges at T4-F8.

4. Infrequent low amplitude sharp transients in the left parietal region at P3.




CLINICAL CORRELATION:



The diffuse background slowing and triphasic activity are nonspecific and indicates a moderate
bihemispheric functional disturbance such as asking variety of metabolic or other generalized
encephalopathies of various etiologies. Focal interictal sharp activity indicates a potential
epileptogenic region in the right anterior temporal area at T4-F8, with questionable minimal
irritative activity also seen infrequently in the left parietal region at P3.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 

This is an abnormal awake and drowsy 1 hour EEG due to 
1. Diffuse background slowing and disorganization

2. Occasional runs of triphasiform activity during drowsiness. 

3. Right frontotemporal sharp-slow wave discharges at T4-F8. 
4. Infrequent low amplitude sharp transients in the left parietal region at P3.

TECHNIQUE:


A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record

EEG BACKGROUND:


The waking background is characterized by the presence of a well organized symmetric mixture of
alpha and beta frequencies, with a symmetric and reactive 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm
(PDR). The normal anterior-to-posterior gradient of frequency and amplitude is present.

Sleep is not captured

None

These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of left temporal cerebral dysfunction.

Sharply contoured theta waves noted over the bitemporal regions synchronously and independently

RECORDING ENVIRONMENT: outpatient


EEG TYPE: 20-40 min, awake and drowsy



HISTORY:

a 44 y.o. female with a history of seizures a few years ago (resolved after started on
Depakote) referred for routine EEG for characterization of seizures, after she had 1 seizure a few days
ago.




MEDICATIONS:

Current Outpatient Prescriptions:


gabapentin (NEURONTIN) 800 mg tablet,

ferrous sulfate 325 mg (65 mg iron) tablet,

DAILY-VITE per tablet, TAKE 1 TABLET DAILY


traMADol (ULTRAM) 50 mg tablet,

zolpidem (AMBIEN) 5 mg tablet,

cyclobenzaprine (FLEXERIL) 10 mg tablet,


diphenhydrAMINE (BENADRYL) 50 mg capsule,

ACETAMINOPHEN/DIPHENHYDRAMINE (TYLENOL PM PO), Take  by mouth.





SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:

A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate
amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is
characterized by a symmetric and reactive 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.




During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen. There is shifting bitemporal theta
slowing in drowsiness.




Sleep is not captured



No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.


EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:


No epileptiform activity is present.


OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None


ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.



EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 78 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is a normal awake and drowsy  routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.





Shifting bitemporal theta slowing is a nonspecific finding, within normal limits for a drowsy state.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:

This is a normal awake and drowsy  routine EEG.


A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.

If clinically warranted, a recording with sleep may be helpful.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is a normal awake and drowsy  routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected. 




Shifting bitemporal theta slowing is a nonspecific finding, within normal limits for a drowsy state.

report:
DATE OF STUDY: 01/18/17

RECORDING ENVIRONMENT: outpatient


EEG TYPE: 20-40 min, awake and asleep





HISTORY:

 a 27 y.o. female with a history of seizures.



MEDICATIONS:

No current outpatient prescriptions on file.


No current facility-administered medications for this visit.




SEDATION: None


TECHNIQUE:


A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.



EEG BACKGROUND:




The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate
amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is
characterized by a symmetric and reactive 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.




During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with synchronous and symmetric vertex waves,
sleep spindles and K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.




No generalized slowing is present.  No focal slowing is present.


EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:


No epileptiform activity is present.


OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None


ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is not performed.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces
symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.



EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 60 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:

This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.




A normal routine EEG does not support or refute the diagnosis of epilepsy.  The lack of epileptiform
discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is a normal awake and asleep routine EEG.  There are no clinical or electrographic events
reported or detected.
